<HEADLINE> Steps Recommended for Improving HK Tour Coordinators's Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 28 (Xinhua) -- A study commissioned by a
Hong Kong-based organization for tour coordinators recommended a
series of steps to improve service professionalism of their trade
so as to maintain high-level service standard.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Association of Registered Tour Coordinators
(HARTCO) said here Monday that it commissioned the study, which
was conducted by the Hong Kong Polytechnic University, financed by
the Services Support Fund managed by the Industry Department of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Government.
</P>
<P>
The study was to evaluate the current professional status of
Hong Kong's tour coordinators and examine the need to upgrade the
industry's service standards by improving skill proficiency and
raising the level of recognition of the industry within the
community.
</P>
<P>
All new entrants to the industry should undergo comprehensive
basic training, pass a basic examination and be formally
registered or licensed, the study recommended.
</P>
<P>
A practical and enforceable monitoring and control system was
recommended to be adopted, including the issuance of photo
identity cards to all registered tour coordinators, random
on-the-spot checks of these cards and the establishment of a
schedule of penalties to punish card holders for unprofessional or
criminal conducts.
</P>
<P>
Other recommendations included setting up a code of
conduct/ethics, based on international standards and practices,
banning of under-cost pricing by tour operators, setting up a task
force to review tour coordinators' heavy reliance on shopping
commissions and raising the overall language proficiency of tour
coordinators, especially in English and Putonghua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
