<HEADLINE> Spartak Boss Romantsev to Coach Russian Natioanl Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Oleg Romantsev of Russian
champions Spartak Moscow was appointed to coach the national team
on Monday, succeeding Anatoly Byshovets who was sacked this month
after just five months in charge.
</P>
<P>
Romantsev, is turning 45 next week, was appointed at a meeting
of the Russian Football Union. He previously led Russia to Euro
96 before being fired after the team performed poorly in the
finals
</P>
<P>
After Russia's sixth change of coach in as many years,
Romantsev had said he would aim to combine the job with staying
on at Spartak.
</P>
<P>
Russia failed to qualify for this year's World Cup finals,
their first absence in 20 years, and now look set to miss the
European championship finals in 2000. Romantsev has said his goal
will be qualification for the 2002 World Cup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
