<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Fire at Iraqi Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
confirmed that its warplanes had attacked an Iraqi target at the
no-fly zone in northern Iraq in response to "an act of aggression"
against U.S. warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Col. Richard Bridges said the incident
happened while patrolling U.S. fighter planes met with Iraqi
"hostile action," "an act of aggression, against U.S. aircraft
flying as part of Operation Northern Watch", in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred at about 1 p.m. local time, just north
of Mosul, according to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton was briefed on the situation early
this morning by Gen. Donald Kerrick, a member of the National
Security Council, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Baghdad said Western warplanes fired missiles at
an air defense site, killing four Iraqi soldiers and injuring
seven others. Iraqi air defenses fired back in response, forcing
the warplanes to fire, the Information Ministry reported in a
statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
