<HEADLINE> Africans Called on to Meet Challenges Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 28 (xinhua) -- The OAU Secretary General
Monday Called on Africans to "draw lessons from the unfortunate
experiences of the past and mobilize the necessary energy and
commitment to meet the challenges ahead".
</P>
<P>
In his New Year Message issued here, Salim Ahmed Salim, chief
of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) describeed the year
1998 as "yet another very difficult year."
</P>
<P>
He said in 1998, millions of African people continued to live
an unenviable life as refugees and displaced persons and millions
more have been suffering from various diseases and that the
overwhelming majority continued to experience the agony of
poverty, with its attendant repercussions of unemployment,
inadequate shelter, lack of education and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
"The sad and revolting images of the bombings in Nairobi and
Dar es Salaam, and in other parts of the continent are still
vivid in our memories," the OAU Chief recalled.
</P>
<P>
Salim said, "furthermore, a large segment of our people,
mainly women and children, have been caught up as victims of the
many conflicts afflicting our continent."
</P>
<P>
After listing conflict situation in Somali, Burundi, Angola,
Western Sahara, Southern Sudan, Comoros, Ethiopia and Eritrea,
Guinea Bissau, Lesotho, the Democratic Republic of Congo and
Sierra Leone, Salim pointed out that "in sum this has been a very
difficult and turbulent year for our continent in so far as our
quest for peace, stability and security is concerned."
</P>
<P>
He noted that "in addressing the scourge of conflict, African
leaders and other concerned Africans have spared no effort in
promoting peaceful solutions to the various crisis in the
continent."
</P>
<P>
"At the core of these efforts has been our continental
organization, which worked hand in hand with African regional
organizations, the United Nations, and the larger international
community to ensure that the necessary attention and focus is
given to the primary issue of peace, security and stability,"
Salim said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "1998 has not been only a year of problems
and calamities," adding, "it also has been a year of modest
achievements and progress."
</P>
<P>
"On the economic front, and despite an unfavorable
international economic environment, many of our countries have
registered positive results, including encouraging improvements
in GDP growth and in per capita incomes," Salim said, adding that
"in the area of economic cooperation and integration, significant
efforts have been made, particularly in some of the African
regions, toward policy harmonization and coordination."
</P>
<P>
Salim hoped in his message that Africans "should draw
inspiration from the achievements made, despite the many
difficulties encountered," concluding that "let us endeavor to
make 1999 a better year for our people" and "let us strive to
take bolder and more imaginative steps toward attaining the much
needed peace in the continent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
