<HEADLINE> Pak, Britain Agree on Regular Annual Consultations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Britain Monday
agreed to institute a framework for regular annual bilateral
consultations and called for further enhancing their cooperation
in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
This was the result coming out from the meeting held here
Monday between visiting British Under Secretary for the Foreign
and Commonwealth Office Sir John Kerr and Pakistan's Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides agreed to institute a framework of bilateral
consultations on a regular annual basis to exchange views on
bilateral relations as well as to promote greater understanding on
global and regional issues of mutual interest," said an official
announcement issued by the Foreign Office after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Kerr called on Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz Monday. During the
meeting, Aziz conveyed his "concern on massive build-up of arms by
India."
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press of Pakistan quoted Aziz as saying that a
just settlement of the Kashmir dispute in accordance with the U.N.
resolutions was imperative "in order to secure a lasting peace in
the region."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was keen to maintain peace and security in the region,
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed all bilateral issues and also exchanged
views on regional and international issues including the Kashmir
dispute, the Afghan crisis and the non-proliferation issue.
</P>
<P>
"During the consultations, both sides discussed in detail the
global and regional issues of mutual interest," said the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad Ahmed told Kerr that Pakistan would welcome engagement
of the U.K. in a dialogue process with India. The third party
mediation would "ensure success of endeavors of the international
community for the establishment of enduring peace in the region,"
said Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
The British under secretary, who arrived here Sunday on a
two-day visit, will leave for New Delhi Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
