<HEADLINE> France Holds UNITA Responsible for Resumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 28 (Xinhua) -- France Monday held the Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) responsible for the
resumption of fighting in Angola since mid-November.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry accused the UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi of not holding his commitment for a ceasefire with the
government forces.
</P>
<P>
"Only a negotiated solution will allow Angola to resume the
road of national reconciliation, which will assure the Angolan
people of stability and development to which they aspire," said
the foreign ministry in a communique.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the fighting sides of Angola to allow
rescuers to do their job near Huambo in central Angola, where a
U.N. plane crashed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ten passengers, all of them members of the U.N. Mission in
Angola, and four crew members disappeared when the Hercule C-130
plane belonging to the trans-Africa air company which they were
riding crashed.
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed in a combat zone between UNITA forces and
Angolan government forces, soon after taking off from Huambo for
Saurimo in eastern Angola.
</P>
<P>
UNITA forces and government forces have been fighting in
central Angola, especially the region near Kuito.  
</P>
</TEXT>
