<HEADLINE> Romania to Upgrade Railway Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 28 (Xinhua) -- As many as seven projects
are included in the railway infrastructure's modernization
priority investments program chiefly focusing on the Helsinki 4th
railways corridor.
</P>
<P>
The railways upgrading works foreseen in the European
agreements Romania is part to, seek to increase circulation speed
on certain railways at 120 km/h for the goods and 160-200 km/h at
persons transportation.
</P>
<P>
The seven projects include to upgrade the
Bucharest-Brasov-Sighisoara-Alba Iulia-Arad-Curtici railway and
the Giurgiu-Videle-Bucharest-Buzau-Pascani-Ungheni line for the
increased speed circulation, to modernize the Bucharest-Constanta
railway of the Helsinki 4th corridor, to restore and develop the
Bucharest-North station, to double and electrify the
Constanta-Mangalia line, to electrify and modernize the
Timisoara-Stamora-Moravita railway and the Bucharest North-Giurgiu
line.
</P>
<P>
The length of the railway in Romania exceeds 22,300 km, of
which 8,600 km are electrified. The main lines of communications
tend to focus on the capital city Bucharest, the biggest railway
center, situated in the south-east. Eight mainlines originate in
Bucharest most of them being connected to the international
routes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
