<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says to Continue to Enforce No-Fly Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Monday that The United States would continue to enforce
no-fly zones in northern and southern parts of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said a U.S. warplane's firing at an Iraqi target was
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
"Our pilots have the authority to protect themselves if they
are attacked. They took appropriate action today in responding to
Iraq's actions," he said in a statement. "We will continue to
enforce the no-fly zones."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's remarks came after he was briefed by a senior
official of the National Security Council that a U.S. fighter
attacked an Iraqi missile battery at the no-fly zone in northern
Iraq in response to "an act of aggression" against U.S. warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Pentagon spokesman Col. Richard Bridges said the
incident happened while patrolling U.S. fighter planes met with
Iraqi "hostile action," "an act of aggression, against U.S.
aircraft flying as part of Operation Northern Watch", in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred at about 1 p.m. local time, just north of
Mosul, according to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the U.S. warplane returned fire after being
attacked by Iraqi surface-to-air missiles. He was happy that the
plane returned safely to its base in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the no-fly zones, established in 1991 after the
Gulf War, "have been and will remain an important part of our
containment policy".
</P>
<P>
"Because we effectively control the skies over Iraq, Saddam
(Hussein) has been unable to use air power against his own
people or lash out again at his neighbors," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Baghdad said Western warplanes fired missiles at
an air defense site, killing four Iraqi soldiers and injuring
seven others. Iraqi air defenses fired back in response, forcing
the warplanes to fire, the Information Ministry reported in a
statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
