<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Ministerial Meeting Put off to Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 28 (Xinhua) -- An Arab foreign ministerial
meeting slated for Wednesday has been put off to next month due to
the rifts among the Gulf states, Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid told reporters that after intensive contacts and
consultations over the past 24 hours, the Arab countries have
agreed to convene the meeting in Cairo on January 24.
</P>
<P>
He said the postponement came at the request of the Gulf
Cooperation Council, a regional alliance comprising Bahrain,
Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief said the league is ready to host the meeting
at any time agreed on by all the Arab states concerned.
</P>
<P>
On December 20, Yemen proposed to hold an emergency Arab summit
to discuss the latest developments in the Arab world, especially
the recent U.S.-British air strikes on Iraq, and seek ways of
restoring Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched missile attacks on Iraq on
December 16-19 with a declared aim of retaliating Iraq's defiance
of the U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The inspections began in 1991 after the Gulf War, triggered by
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, to ensure Iraq clears off all
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministerial meeting is designed to discuss the
Yemen's call.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and other Gulf Arab countries have said they have no
objection to any envisaged summit.
</P>
<P>
However, Kuwait boycotted a meeting of the Arab Parliamentary
Union held Sunday in Amman to discuss the Iraqi crisis following
the U.S.-British attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
