<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes in Turkey Fire at Iraqi Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- A fleet of U.S. warplanes took
off from southern Turkey and fired at an Iraqi target at the
no-fly zone in northern Iraq, Turkish sources told Xinhua Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that "eight F-16 fighter planes took off from
the Incirlik Airbase in Adana, southern Turkey at noon and
attacked at an Iraqi target in the no-fly zone."
</P>
<P>
A U.S. diplomat, who asked not to be named, said that "Iraq
launched missiles against the U.S. warplanes patrolling in the
no-fly zone in northern Iraq and the U.S. warplanes launched
counter-attacks against the Iraqi target."
</P>
<P>
Reports from Baghdad said U.S. warplanes flying from Turkey
violated Iraqi airspace in the so-called no-fly zone in northern
Iraq and fired missiles at an air defense site, killing four Iraqi
soldiers and wounding seven others.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi soldiers fought back courageously, forcing the warplanes
to flee, the Iraqi News Agency quoted a military spokesman as
saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish Foreign Ministry issued no statement on
whether the U.S. warplanes took off from the Incirlik Airbase to
fire at the Iraqi target.
</P>
<P>
Multinational troops led by the U.S. used the Incirlik Airbase
to bombard northern Iraq during the Gulf War in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
