<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sends Reinforcements to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has sent 600 more
soldiers to Sierra Leone to reinforce defense against rebels who
threatened to march on the capital Freetown, a spokesman for the
west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG said Monday.
</P>
<P>
A report from the capital of the west African country said the
reinforcements, who arrived on Sunday evening, increased the size
of the Nigerian-led troops to around 12,000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking as Sierra Leone's neighbors are holding talks in Cote
d'Ivoire on the conflict, the spokesman said more reinforcements
and equipment would arrive during the week ahead.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports said that Revolutionary United Front rebels
and renegade soldiers, who ousted elected President Ahmed Kabbah
from May 1997 to March 1998, had attacked Makeni, a northern town
some 100 km northeast of the capital Freetown and taken control
of it.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG spokesmen in Freetown declined comment on the state of
the battle for the town, which began on December 23. Rebels
entered the town over Christmas. But ECOMOG said Saturday that it
had expelled them again.
</P>
<P>
The rebels took up arms in 1991. They agreed on a peace deal
with Kabbah after his 1996 election but it unravelled and they
rallied to the 1997 coup.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG restored Kabbah to power in March 1997 but the rebels
and their allies in the ousted military junta regrouped
up-country. They have intensified their raids in the east and
stepped up attacks in the country since RUF leader Foday Sankoh
was sentenced to death for treason last October.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have around 15,000 to 20,000 soldiers, including
youngsters reportedly press-ganged into fighting for them.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah can count on the support of a traditional hunters'
militia, the Kamajors, who number 25,000 to 30,000, apart from
the ECOMOG troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Job Cuts Planned by German Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Half of Germany's industrial and
business sectors plan to cut jobs in 1999, according to a survey
published Monday by the Institute for German Economic Research
(IW).
</P>
<P>
The survey of 42 industrial and business sectors revealed that
only four planned to create new jobs in Germany next year. These
were the tourism, skilled crafts, rubber and moving sectors.
</P>
<P>
But executives in 21 sectors said they planned to cut their
workforces in 1999. Among those pledging cuts were such key
branches as banking, insurance, construction, food processing,
oil, electricity and steel.
</P>
<P>
Companies in the remaining branches said they planned no
changes in employment levels. These included the important
chemicals, aerospace, automobile, ship-building, machinery, optics
and electronics sectors.
</P>
<P>
German unemployment hit a post-World War II record of 12.6
percent - 4.8 million unemployed - earlier this year. The rate has
since sunk to 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The IW said uncertainty over Chancellor Gerhard Schoreder's
policies and tougher competition from abroad were reflected in
corporate investment plans.
</P>
<P>
"Many concerns have temporarily suspended previously planned
investment and, above all, are keeping open the option of more
foreign investment," said the IW in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The new center-left government has said it will not cut
corporate taxes until 2002. Following sharp protests from business
leaders Schroeder backed down and said if enough revenue was
available the cuts might go ahead in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
