<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Says Europe Divided over Nuclear Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Plans by Germany's new
center-left government to close nuclear power stations have put
Bonn at odds with other European countries, a German government
publication admitted Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The use of nuclear power divides Europe," said Germany's
Federal Press Office in its Europa Interview monthly.
</P>
<P>
France is the leading nuclear nation in Europe and generates 78
percent of its electricity from 58 nuclear stations, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Belgium was the second biggest nuclear user, producing 60
percent of its electricity from seven stations, followed by Sweden
which draws 46 percent of its power from 12 stations.
</P>
<P>
Germany, which is fourth ranked, produces 32 percent of its
electricity from 19 nuclear stations.
</P>
<P>
But nuclear station closure means German electricity will have
to come from other sources, said the report.
</P>
<P>
With the liberalization of European energy markets in 1999,
electricity can be imported. Although the report does not spell it
out, this means electricity from French nuclear stations could
wind up being exported to Germany to make up for shortfalls caused
by German nuclear closures.
</P>
<P>
The heavy use of nuclear power by some E.U. states contrasts
with Italy and Denmark which have no nuclear power plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
