<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian-Israeli Clashes Erupt over House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Violent clashes broke out at
a Palestinian village in the West Bank Monday as Israeli soldiers
tore down two Palestinian houses as "illegal buildings."
</P>
<P>
Israeli TV Channel One showed a middle-aged Palestinian man, a
child in his arms, was at the door of his house trying to block
the soldiers. He fell to the ground when the soldiers forcefully
evicted him.
</P>
<P>
A bulldozer soon leveled the house and a shack. Angered, dozens
of villagers threw stones at the soldiers, who responded with tear
gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
With his wife crying besides the ruins, the Palestinian man
shouted in rage, vowing he will revenge and will teach his
children the way of Hamas, the resistance movement that has staged
a series of deadly attacks against Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said an Israeli soldier and a border policeman
were injured in the clashes. At least one Palestinian youth was
seen bleeding on his forehead on the TV.
</P>
<P>
Israel has stepped up its campaign to demolish Palestinian
houses in the occupied territories over the past year as a way to
tighten control there.
</P>
<P>
It claimed that the houses it demolished were illegal ones
because the Palestinians had not got permits before they were
constructed. The Palestinians argue that it was almost impossible
for them to get a permit at any time.
</P>
<P>
The demolition of houses and the confiscation of Palestinian
lands for building by-pass roads for Jewish settlers in the West
Bank have triggered sporadic clashes between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the military wing of Hamas vowed in a
statement Monday to go on with "armed struggle" against Israel,
threatening to conduct more attacks if Israel continues to arrest
Palestinians and confiscate their lands.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, a petrol bomb was thrown outside a religious
school in the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem, but caused no
damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
