<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Outlines Future Foreign Policy Tasks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
positively assessed the diplomatic activities of the Foreign
Ministry in 1998 and outlined its tasks for 1999, according to the
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov on Monday said at a joint
press conference with visiting Armenian counterpart Vartan
Oskanyan that Yeltsin has formulated the main foreign affairs
guidelines and priorities for processes in the CIS.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed the need for ensuring a political
settlement of international conflicts to prevent an escalation of
tension and confrontation, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ivanov, Yeltsin also noted the tasks concerning
the regime of non-proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Serious work will have to be done to boost Russia's relations
with European countries, primarily through the European Union,
Ivanov said. As part of these efforts, Boris Yeltsin is expected
to make a visit to France at the end of January, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov also said that Russia attaches great significance to the
Russian-U.S. dialogue, regarding it as an important factor of
stability in the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Russia will continue to actively develop its relations with
Asian partners, including China, India, and Japan, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Russia will also facilitate the settlement of crises in the
Middle East, in the Gulf area and other regions in order to find
political solutions through concerted international efforts
respectful of the supremacy of international law, said Ivanov.
</P>
</TEXT>
