<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Local Elections to Be Held as Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- An election spokesman Monday
said the gubernatorial elections would be held on January 9 as
schedule, adding, "the exercise is not postponed and our offices
nationwide are expected to start screening the candidates."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the Independent National electoral Commission
(INEC) announced here that about 3,075 candidates were expected
to be screened nationwide within the next three days by INEC for
next week's gubernatorial and house of assembly elections.
</P>
<P>
And 108 of candidates are for gubernatorial elections while
the other 2,967 are for elections into the 36 state houses of
assembly in the January 9 elections, the second in the set of
four elections under the current transition program, he added.
</P>
<P>
Next week's elections will not take place in Nigerian capital
of Abuja which is treated as a mayoralty and already has a
minister.
</P>
<P>
Under an election guidance, House of Assembly candidates
should be at least 30 years old while those going for
governorship should be over 35.
</P>
<P>
The three registered political parties of the Alliance for
Democracy, All People's Party and People's Democratic Party
concluded their primaries last week to elect those whose names
were submitted to INEC by December 23 to contest the 36
gubernatorial and 989 house of assembly seats in next week's
elections
</P>
<P>
January 9 elections will be followed by national assembly
elections on February 20 while the presidential election will
take place a week later on February 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
