<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. African States Meet to Discuss S. Leone Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- West African states met in
Abidjan Monday for emergency talks on renewed civil war in Sierra
Leone, stressing the need for dialog between the warring sides, a
report reaching here from the Ivorian commercial capital said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held by the special committee of the economic
community of west African states (ECOWAS) after Nigeria rushed
600 more troops to Sierra Leone over the weekend to reinforce the
west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG following the alleged
seizure of a northeastern town of Makeni by rebels.
</P>
<P>
Togo's Foreign Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh, chairing the
talks, said national reconciliation was the key to peace in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"We must insist on the necessity to organize a true dialog --
a frank and sincere dialog between Sierra Leone's feuding
brothers," Koffigoh was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Previous meetings of the committee had concentrated on
protecting elected President Ahmad Kabbah, who was restored to
power last March after a military junta kept him in exile for 10
months.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian-led troops evicted the junta and its Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) allies from Freetown, clearing the way for
Kabbah's return.
</P>
<P>
But regrouped junta loyalists and RUF rebels have renewed
their campaign against Kabbah's government recently and
threatened to march on the capital of Freetown after taking
Makeni, a town 100 km northeast of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said the new stress on dialog reflected concern over
the future role of regional superpower Nigeria in Sierra Leone
peace-keeping.
</P>
<P>
"There is a growing fear in the region that a new civilian
government taking over in Nigeria in May next year may not want
to shoulder the burden of peace-keeping in Sierra Leone," a west
African diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS Secretary-General Lansana Kouyate said Nigeria demanded
the emergency meeting after rebels attacked close to Freetown
last week, sparking panic in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The latest Nigerian reinforcement boosted ECOMOG to around
12,000 troops as against about 15,000 to 20,000 rebel soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Former colonial ruler Britain and the United States, which
were also represented at the meeting, evacuated their citizens
from Freetown last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
