<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African Leaders to Meet in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of Kenya,
Tanzania and Uganda will meet in Arusha town in northern Tanzania
next month to review progress of the two-year-old East African
Cooperation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
The summit, second of its kind, will discuss among other
things, the suggestion of signing a treaty for the cooperation
and a request by Rwanda to join the regional grouping which
currently comprises only three countries.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the East African Secretariat in Arusha said
Monday that the meeting is scheduled between January 18 and 21.
The last summit was held in mid 1997 when the leaders met to
revive the the cooperation of east African countries.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the meeting next week will
also review decisions endorsed by the Permanent Tripartite
Commission, the highest decision making body of EAC, whose
chairman is Tanzania's Minister of Foreign Affairs and
International Cooperation Jakaya Kikwete.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the EAC is broad, covering regional cooperation
in political, economic, social, cultural, security and legal
affairs. In the short run, EAC member countries will give
priority to economic cooperation, which is crucial to political
cooperation in the long run.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the three member states have held not less
than 40 sectoral meeting aimed at harmonizing policies for the
establishment of a single market and investment area over the
past months.
</P>
<P>
The meetings have covered harmonization of fiscal and monetary
policies, movement of people and vehicles across borders within
the region, development of regional economic infrastructure,
telecommunications, energy, roads, railways, civil aviation and
shipping.
</P>
<P>
Other important sectoral meetings discussed security as well
as legal and judicial affairs.
</P>
<P>
EAC's predecessor, the defunct East African Community,
collapsed in 1977 due to the divergence of economic policies then
pursued by the member states, the continued perception of
disproportionate sharing of benefits accrued form economic
integration and other factors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
