<HEADLINE> Pangalos: Conditions Created to Reassess Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 28 (Xinhua) -- New conditions had been created
in light of which the Russian-made S-300 missile issue must be
reassessed, Greece's Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos said in
an interview with a local daily newspaper Monday.
</P>
<P>
The conditions referred to by Pangalos were the two resolutions
on Cyprus adopted last week by the U.N. Security Council and a
statement by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions demanded lowering tension and resuming
inter-communal negotiations in Cyprus while Clinton pledged to
take all necessary steps to support the resolutions with an aim to
end the tragic division of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos added that the final decision concerning the S-300
missiles would be taken by Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and
the country's National Council but also seriously taking into
consideration Greece's views.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greece's Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said Monday that the issue of whether the missiles
would eventually be deployed in Cyprus or the southern Greek
island of Crete was a technical matter which would be dealt with
the governments of Cyprus and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an army post on the Greek-Turkish border,
Tsohatzopoulos said that the responsibility of Cyprus and Greece
in Tuesday's talks would reflect the steadfast choice of
strengthening the joint defense of both countries, the
strengthening of their apability to stand firmly and defend the
prospects for Cyprus' accession to the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Clerides arrives in Athens later Monday to
discuss with Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis the planned
installation by Nicosia of the S-300 anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Clerides will agree to deploy the missiles
in Crete instead of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus announced last year plans to purchase and deploy the
missiles from Russia with an aim to bolster its defense, but
Turkey has threatened to use force to prevent the missile
installation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
