<HEADLINE> Rwandan-Ugandan Army Clashes in Congo (K) Denied. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan army spokesman Major
Emmanuel Ndahiro has dismissed a report by a Ugandan paper saying
that there was an exchange of fires between Rwandan and Ugandan
soldiers stationed in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
An Independent Ugandan paper, The Monitor, reported that 30
Rwandan Patriotic Army soldiers died in a fire exchange with the
Ugandans deployed in the Democratic Republic of Congo, a special
story reaching here Monday from Rwandan News Agency (RNA) said.
</P>
<P>
The Monitor Sunday quoted a Ugandan army officer, whose name
was withheld, as saying that eight Ugandan soldiers were also
killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
"It a mere fabrication, and we cannot understand the rationale
behind it," Ndahiro was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Up to now there has been no physical fight, let alone a fire
exchange," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan army spokesman said that the reported incident
could not have taken place since Rwandan troops are not present
in northeastern Congo, where the Ugandan People's Defense Force
soldiers are based.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan paper had alleged that the row between Rwandan and
Ugandan soldiers stemmed from the fact that the two armies
backing different factions of Congolese rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan officer, quoted by The Monitor, claimed that while
Uganda is favorable to the newly-born Congolese Liberation
Movement (MLC) led by Jean Pierre Bemba, Rwanda allegedly
supports the main rebel movement, the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD) chaired by professor Ernest Wamba dia Wamba.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandans are said to accuse the RCD of being unpopular,
while MLC is said to be dynamic and has proven it can raise the
Congolese people against president Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Ndahiro dismissed any disagreement between Rwanda and Uganda
concerning the on-going conflict in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
"We have officially agreed not to support any faction,"
Ndahiro said.
</P>
<P>
The RCD Deputy-Chairman, Arthur Z'ahidi Ngoma also blasted The
Monitor's report saying that there is no antagonism whatsoever
between their main allies, Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Ngoma indicated that allegations that RCD is unpopular is
groundless, "since we have been enjoying warm welcome in towns
and localities which fell under our control". 
</P>
</TEXT>
