<HEADLINE> Likud, Labor Agree upon Election Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel's two main parties,
the Likud and the Labor, reached a compromise Monday on the date
for early elections, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
After hours of talks in the evening, representatives from the
two parties agreed to hold the elections on May 17, and a second
round, if needed, on June 1, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the Likud had favored a date as close as
possible to May 4, the deadline of the five-year interim period
set in the Oslo accords between Israel and the Palestinians and
when Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has said he will declare an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has reportedly wanted to use
what he called the unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state
as a card to strengthen his position in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the Labor Party had demanded that the elections
be held as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
But recent reports said Labor leader Ehud Barak also wanted
the elections to be held in a later date in hopes that the
reputation of another challenger, the popular former Chief of
Staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, would ebb as time drags on. Barak
denied the reports.
</P>
<P>
Israeli parliament passed the first reading of a bill calling
for early elections on December 21. If the date agreed upon by the
two largest parties is approved by the law committee of the
parliament, the bill will be presented for its second and third
reading in the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
