<HEADLINE> Turkey Watchful of Latest Strike in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is closely watching the
latest developments of the Iraqi crisis after the United States
fired missiles at an Iraqi target in northern Iraq early Monday,
local media reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military and Foreign Ministry have been
maintaining constant contacts and keeping each other informed on
the development of the confrontation between the U.S. and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry officials said that the U.S. warplanes
patrolling in the no-fly zone in northern Iraq fired back at Iraqi
air defense sites after being exposed to surface-to-air missile
attacks from the Iraqi sites.
</P>
<P>
They added that the U.S. aircraft, taking off from Turkey, were
conducting the "Operation Northern Watch," an ongoing operation in
which U.S. and British warplanes stationed at the Incirlik Air
Base in Adana, southern Turkey, monitor the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led allies set up the no-fly zone in northern Iraq
after the 1991 Gulf War allegedly to protect the Kurds there.
</P>
<P>
Multinational troops led by the U.S. used the Incirlik air
base in Adana in bombarding northern Iraq during the Gulf War
triggered by Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said that four Iraqi soldiers were killed and seven
others wounded during Monday's attack, the first casualties
officially reported by Iraq after the U.S. and Britain concluded
on December 19 their four nights of air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
