<HEADLINE> Defected KR Leaders Say Sorry to Cambodian people </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Defecting Khmer Rouge
leaders Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea said Tuesday they were very
very sorry to Cambodian people.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea said at a press conference held in
the Royal Phnom Penh Hotel that they were very very sorry to the
Cambodian people for their misery and suffering.
</P>
<P>
"Normally, I am very regrettable not only for the lives of the
people but also lives of the animals. We are very regrettable,"
Nuon Chea said.
</P>
<P>
"But we are also the hostages and victims of the civil war just
like Cambodian people. So we should, as Prime Minister Hun Sen had
put forward, dig a hole and bury the past and look ahead into the
21st century," Khieu Samphan said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about what their reaction to set up an international
tribunal to prosecute Khmer Rouge leaders, Khieu said Cambodia's
issues should be resolved with Cambodia's way and in accordance
with the Paris Peace Accords signed by all factions on October 23,
1991. "Please, let our people and nation resolve our own
problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To let bygones be bygones is the best solution for our country
because it is the only way to reach national reconciliation. We
will do our best to end the war and maintain the national
reconciliation," added Khieu.
</P>
<P>
The nominal KR leader Khieu Samphan, 67, was in good health but
top ideologue Nuon Chea, 71, looked very weak.
</P>
<P>
They arrived here Tuesday morning with their families and met
with Prime Minister Hun Sen and President of the National Assembly
Prince Ranariddh separately who gave them warm welcome and praised
their defection to the royal government.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Samphan told the reporters at the Royal Phnom Penh Hotel
after the meeting that he was very happy to return to the capital,
saying it reflected the national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
It was Khieu's first time returning to the capital since early
1994 when the Khmer Rouge was outlawed by the royal government.
</P>
<P>
Nuon Chea has not been in Phnom Penh since the toppling of the
Khmer Rouge regime in 1979 when Vietnamese forces invaded and sent
the movement to jungle bases.
</P>
<P>
The two defected to the royal government on Friday after talked
to Prime Minister Hun Sen through telephone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
