<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Natural Conservation Land Up to Average World Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The ratio of legally conserved
natural land to the total land area of China has reached 7.64
percent, up the average world level of 7 percent, said a Chinese
wildlife-protection official today -- International Day
for Biological Diversity.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yongfan, deputy director of the Department of Wildlife
Protection under the State Administration of Forestry, said that
the establishment of nature reserves is still the primary method
of maintaining bio-diversity worldwide, and the number of nature
reserves has a significant meaning for global efforts to protect
bio-diversity.
</P>
<P>
China now has 926 nature reserves, while only twenty years
ago, when China began its reform and opening-up drive, there were
but 34 such reserves in the country, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"About 100 new reserves will be set up every year for the next
several years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said he was also very proud of China's
international cooperation in bio-diversity protection. For
example, the Global Environment Facility's first bio-diversity
project in China -- the China Nature Reserve Management Project --
has achieved good results since it was launched in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"In our nature reserves we have largely improved field
patrolling and have established good partnership relations with
neighboring villagers; and we have also successfully transformed a
large stretch of forest with rich bio-diversity resources from a
logging area into a new national nature reserve," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Susan Chen, a senior ecologist with the World Bank, expressed
her satisfaction with the cooperative spirit shown by the Chinese
bio-diversity protection officials. "They are among the best
counterparts I have ever met in the world," she said.
</P>
<P>
The International Day for Biological Diversity was started in
1994 by the United Nations to mark the International Convention on
Bio-Diversity that went into effect on December 29, 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
