<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worst Part of Pak Economic Crisis Over: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Finance Minister
Ishaq Dar said Tuesday that the worst part of the economic crisis
faced by Pakistan is over and key economic indicators are
improving.
</P>
<P>
"We have successfully managed to take the economy out of the
wood. Inshallah (by the wish of God), in the coming months, the
economy would move towards growth and stability," Dar said at a
press briefing here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Considering the economic difficulties faced by Pakistan as a
result of economic sanctions, "we have managed to maintain growth
and macro-stability on the one hand and have met our commitments
to preferred creditors on debt servicing liabilities on the
other," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Dar expressed the hope that Pakistan will continue to meet its
commitments on debt servicing in coming months.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said that despite difficulties it has been
possible for Pakistan to maintain industrial growth of three
percent during the first four months (July-October) of the current
fiscal year as against a decline of 1.3 percent in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
"The performance of industrial sector is fairly broad-based.
Items belonging to consumer, manufactured and electronic goods
registered substantial growth," Dar added.
</P>
<P>
On the revenue side, Dar said, gross revenue collection by the
Central Board of Revenue from July to November amounted to 123.7
billion rupees (2.7 billion U.S. dollars) which is almost five
percent higher than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said that monetary expansion has been kept in
check. Money supply during July-November period increased by 1.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation continues to be low. The Consumer Price
Index (CPI) during July-November period increased by 6.6 percent
as compared to 10.2 percent in the corresponding period of last
year, said Dar.
</P>
<P>
Trade imbalance during the period has improved by 46 percent
from 1.021 billion dollars to 554 million dollars, said Dar,
adding that in fact, the trade deficit is lowest in the last six
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
