<HEADLINE> Drug-related Crimes Rampant in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Drug-related crime is still
rampant in Russia, posing a serious threat to the country's
public order, Russian Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total number of drug-trafficking and other related crimes
reached 170,000 and those involving adolescents rose two percent,
the Itar-Tass news agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 percent of those crimes were violent in nature.
Law enforcement agencies cleared 88,000 of the reported cases and
62,000 suspects were detained by police, Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that the large-scale operation, codenamed
Whirlwind, launched by the Interior Ministry last week was a
success, with the amount of work handled by police being doubled
or trebled during that period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
