<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Suffers Heavy Losses by Soeharto Abuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian state suffered
financial losses totaling 2,850 billion rupiah (one U.S. dollar
equals 8,000 rupiah) by corrupt, collusive and nepotistic (KKN)
practices involving former president Soeharto, high-ranking
officials of his government and his cronies, a senior cabinet
minister announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The abuses were committed at five ministries and three
non-ministerial state agencies, Coordinating Minister for
Development Supervision/State Reform Hartarto said at a press
conference after meeting with President B.J. Habibie at Merdeka
Palace.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto said the finding was the result of the second phase of
a government effort to eradicate the abuses.
</P>
<P>
Both the attorney general and the head of Agency for the
Financial Auditing of National Development (BPKP) had begun to
take concrete and intensive measures to end the irregularities, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The KKN practices mainly consisted of the granting of special
facilities and privileges by the ministers and state enterprises
concerned private economic units or limited liability companies
owned or controlled by members of Soeharto's family or his close
associates, Hartarto said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister for State Enterprises Tanri Abeng said the
government had canceled 79 KKN-tainted projects.
</P>
<P>
The 79 had been part of a total of 167 projects his office had
previously suspended of having been created through KKN.
</P>
<P>
Mine and Energy Minister Kuntoro Mangkusubroto said on the same
occasion, his ministry had identified 152 projects run by
state-owned petroleum and natural gas company Pertamina as having
come about through KKN practices.
</P>
<P>
The KKN-tainted projects had caused Pertamina financial losses
totaling 64.7 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Public Works Minister Rachmadi Bambang
Sumadhijo said his ministry had investigated 107 tollway
construction packages suspected of having been drawn up through
KKN.
</P>
<P>
"Some 24 feasibility studies and toll road investment packages
worth a total of 15.83 trillion rupiah have been revoked," he
said.
</P>
<P>
BPKP Head Sudarjono reported that in the period 1993-1998, his
office passed on 102 corruption cases to the Attorney General's
Office for further prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The cases had caused the government financial losses totaling
over 668.98 billion rupiah. Most of the cases had occurred at the
Home Affairs Ministry, the Education and Culture Ministry, the
Cooperatives Ministry and the Agriculture Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Andi M. Ghalib said that until November 30,
1998, his office had handled 1,604 cases related with KKN
practices.
</P>
<P>
The cases had caused the government to incur financial losses
amounting to 1.5 trillion rupiah but his office's action had
prevented the loss of 46.6 billion rupiah, Ghalib added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
