<HEADLINE> Synchronized Diving to Be Inclusion in Sydney Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 29 (Xinhhua) -- After synchronized swimming
has been listed as an Olympic event, synchronized diving is now
likely to be included on the program of the 2000 Sydney Olympics,
the swimming's world governing body FINA said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
FINA said that, upon its recommendation, Sydney organizers had
petitioned the International Olympic Committee to accept the
addition of the event.
</P>
<P>
The IOC executive board will announce its decision in March,
FINA said in its latest newsletter.
</P>
<P>
Synchronized diving, recognized since 1995, is now included in
most major international competitions, including the world
championships.
</P>
<P>
The event involves divers plunging into the water side by side
from either the 10-meter platform or from parallel 3-meter
springboards. The divers are judged on individual technical
skills and the ability to coordinate their movements and enter
the water together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
