<HEADLINE> Shanghai Stock Investors Welcome Securities Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Promulgation of China's first
Securities Law was today's hot topic among stock investors in
Shanghai, China's biggest stock-trading center.
</P>
<P>
China's top legislature, the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, passed the Securities Law today in Beijing. It
will take effect on July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The Securities Law will help standardize stock market
activities including stock floatation and trading, and makes us
confident in the future of China's stock market," said Jing
Zhaodi, an employee of a Shanghai listed company.
</P>
<P>
Mangers of listed companies agree that with further regulation
of the stock market, they can compete more responsibly and provide
better services for their investors.
</P>
<P>
For stockbrokers, adoption of the Securities Law will also have
benefits.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoming, deputy general manager of the China Securities
Co. Ltd. Shanghai branch, noted that China's stock market has
experienced many vicissitudes since it first came into being at
the start of the 1990's. "The promulgation of the Securities Law will
rectify the shortcoming that China had no real fundmental law for
regulating the stock market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The impending Securities Law did not seem to affect trading on
the Shanghai Stock Exchange today, as the composite stock index
closed at 1155.878, down only four points from yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
