<HEADLINE> China-Made Hi-tech System Exported to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Science and
Technology announced here today that China has exported to the
United States, Canada and several other countries its
self-developed portable mobile office automation
telecommunications (OAT) system terminals.
</P>
<P>
An official with the ministry said at a news conference here
that the export of the high-tech telecommunications product, listed
among the country's major high-tech projects, indicates a major
breakthrough for the nation's telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the latest orders for the systems are valued at 68
million U.S. dollars. This is the first group of China's high-tech
products to enter into the U.S. and European markets.
</P>
<P>
The system, weighing 1.2 kilograms and about the size of a
dictionary, can copy, scan, fax, store and print documents
anywhere, anytime.
</P>
<P>
The universal telecommunications packet system was jointly
developed by the Hebei-based Hengda Wireless Communications Group
and the Datang Telecom Technology Corporation. The joint venture
of the two companies has signed contracts with Motorola and
several other well known telecommunications giants that includes
supplying parts for the OAT system.
</P>
<P>
The Hengda Group, a high-tech venture in the Shijiazhuang
High-Tech Development Zone in northern China's Hebei Province, has
built production bases in the U.S., Canada, Singapore and Japan,
while the Datang Company is a listed high-tech venture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
