<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Foreign Exchange Reserves Cross 1B Dollar Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's foreign exchange
reserves have increased to 1.021 billion U.S. dollars after
receiving 324.6 million dollars from the U.S. on account of F-16
aircraft, Finance Minister Ishaq Dar announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in Pakistan's foreign exchange reserves is "a very
positive development," Dar said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said that since May this year when Pakistan conducted its
nuclear blasts, this is for the first time that the country's
foreign exchange reserves have crossed the "psychological
barriers" of one billion dollar mark.
</P>
<P>
"Under the circumstances, the government has been able to
manage the macro-economic situation in a reasonably good way
despite a world-wide recession, Southeast Asian turmoil and
contraction of the Japanese economy," said Dar.
</P>
<P>
Dar categorically denied the assertion that the government had
purchased the foreign exchange from the market at very high rates.
</P>
<P>
"The buoyancy in foreign exchange reserves is due to
repatriation of exports proceeds, increased remittances and the
routine exercises we are following since November 7 to improve the
reserves level," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, Dar said that 324.6 million dollars
Pakistan received from the U.S. on account of F-16 aircraft would
be used for balance of payments support and not for the immediate
defense purchases.
</P>
<P>
To another question, Dar said Pakistan's foreign exchange
reserves would be around 900 million dollars by the end of
December this year despite making payments of 60 million dollars
to the International Monetary Fund and the World bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
