<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rare-Earth Exports Not Affected by Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts said today
that the Asian financial crisis will not decrease China's
rare-earth exports, on the contrary, the strong yuan will maintain
world rare-earth prices.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Europe and Japan are the three biggest
buyers of China's rare-earth products, and experts point out that
the U.S. and Europe are expected to maintain their imports since
their economies have not been affected by the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which is still in economic recession, will not reduce
its import because rare earth is one of its most important
industrial material, and only takes a small share in its total
imported products, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Japanese Customs Office indicates that
the country bought 2,208 tons of rare earth from China in the first
two months of 1998, an increase of 30 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
China is the world largest rare-earth producer and exporter. It
is expected that China will produce 53,000 tons of rare earth in
1998, 31,400 of which is for the overseas market.
</P>
<P>
China produces 60 to 70 percent of all the world's rare-earth
products, enough to basically meet both domestic and overseas
demands and help maintain rare-earth prices at a rational level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
