<HEADLINE> Beijing Bans Cars Lacking Emissions Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital will spare
no efforts to control air pollution caused by automobiles which
lack emission-control devices, since exhaust fumes have become a
major threat to the health of Beijingers.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qi, executive vice-mayor of Beijing, said the city will not
allow cars whose emissions do not meet state environmental
protection standards.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks at an event during which more than 3,600
discarded automobiles were destroyed, a small portion of the
city's estimated 33,000 cars abandoned just this year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that about 1.35 million automobiles
are now on the streets of Beijing. The nitrogen oxide in the
automobile fumes has long been engandering the health of the
local population because up to now few precautions were taken to
prevent gas pollution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
