<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Very High" Roadside API Recorded in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Environmental Protection
Department of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
Tuesday recorded a roadside Air Pollution Index (API) of 104 at
the Causeway Bay air quality monitoring station on Hong Kong
Island.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the highest API figures so far recorded since
the APIs were first recorded earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Another roadside station at Mong Kok, Kowloon, recorded an API
of 77. For the general ambient stations, the API ranged from 59
to 76.
</P>
<P>
Causeway Bay, one of Hong Kong's busiest commercial areas, is
notorious for its poor air quality due to very heavy traffic and
the fact that the area is surrounded by numerous high-rise
buildings.
</P>
<P>
When the roadside API exceeds 100 and reaches the "very high"
band, people with heart or respiratory illnesses should avoid
prolonged stay in roads and streets with heavy traffic, Principal
Environmental Protection Officer Leung Pak-ming said.
</P>
<P>
"If it is necessary to stay in such places, they should reduce
physical exertion as far as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Leung said there was no need for the general public to
take any special measure.
</P>
<P>
He said that air pollution reached the "very high" band since
the nitrogen dioxide in vehicle emissions, particularly from
diesel vehicles, was not dispersing sufficiently under the very
still wind conditions due to the special environmental conditions
in the area.
</P>
<P>
But the situation was expected to improve Wednesday, Leung
said.
</P>
<P>
"The weather forecast has expected the wind to become fresh
overnight. This would help nitrogen dioxide to disperse more
readily and we hope air quality would be better tomorrow. The API
forecast for tomorrow is 60 to 80 for the general air quality
stations and 75 to 95 for the roadside air quality stations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government has decided to take measures to battle the
deteriorating air quality, including gradually replacing all the
existing diesel engine-powered taxis with ones powered by
liquefied petroleum gas.
</P>
<P>
The API is a simple way of describing air pollution levels to
provide timely information about air pollution to the public and
to enhance awareness. The EPD has been reporting since June 1995
the daily API and making a forecast for the following day. In
Hong Kong the API converts air pollution data from several types
of pollutants into a value ranging from 0 to 500.
</P>
<P>
The API forecast serves also as an alert to the public before
the onset of serious air pollution episodes. It helps the general
public, especially susceptible groups such as those with heart or
respiratory illnesses, to consider taking precautionary measures
when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Starting from early 1998, the EPD is also reporting the urban
roadside APIs. The levels of air pollution at busy urban
roadsides are represented by the urban roadside air quality
monitoring stations in Mong Kok, Central and Causeway Bay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
