<HEADLINE> Senior Official Expelled from Party for Corruption (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A former vice-governor of
central China's Hubei Province has been expelled from the
Communist Party of China (CPC) for corruption and serious
violation of Party disciplines and laws, the CPC Central
Commission for Discipline Inspection announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The CPC Central Committee approved the decision to deprive
Meng Qingping, who had already been arrested according to law by
procuratorial organs, of Party membership, said the Central
Commission for Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
Investigators found that from 1989 to the end of 1996, Meng and
his wife Guo Xiuying took bribes worth some 225,000 yuan (about
28,000 U.S. dollars) and 100,000 Hong Kong dollars (about 14,000
U.S. dollars) from several businessmen in the southernmost island
province of Hainan. In return, Meng used his power to help these
businessmen obtain huge profits through illegal land deals.
</P>
<P>
Meng, who once served as vice-governor of Hainan before being
transferred to Hubei in April 1993, was also accused of leading an
extremely corrupt life and having sexual relations with many
women.
</P>
</TEXT>
