<HEADLINE> Iraq Condemns Deferment of AL Ministerial Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Ministry on
Tuesday expressed astonishment at and condemnation of deferment of
a ministerial meeting by the secretary-general of the Arab League
(AL).
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman said there are two aspects in this
resolution arousing astonishment and denunciation.
</P>
<P>
"First, this resolution contradicted the traditions and rules
of the AL's action," said the spokesman. He added the ministerial
meeting should be held in the scheduled venue and date at the
approval of the simple majority and with the attendance of those
who wish to attend.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that AL Secretary-General Esmat Abdul Mejuid
has announced that the AL decided to postpone the foreign
ministerial consultative meeting till February 24. It was due to
be held on December 30.
</P>
<P>
Mejuid attributed the postponement to a demand put forward by
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)'s countries. GCC groups Kuwait,
Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and the United Arab Emirates
(UAE).
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said this is the first time that AL
defers a meeting because of the unwillingness of minority to
attend it.
</P>
<P>
"This constitutes a serious precedent by the secretary-general
of the AL," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the second aspect is that the
secretary-general justified his decision with the desire of the
GCC.
</P>
<P>
He said the secretary-general himself declared that 17 Arab
countries had agreed to attend the meeting, and among those
who did not give their opinion regarding the meeting were only
three countries.
</P>
<P>
UAE has reportedly criticized the postponement of the meeting,
and has reiterated support to hold an Arab summit with the aim of
discussing the recent U.S.-British aggression on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ten days ago, the U.S. and Britain launched four nights of air
strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The thing that has astonished us is that those who asked for
deferring the meeting will meet in Riyadh tomorrow to discuss the
situation," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
It was not Iraq but the secretary-general himself called
for holding this meeting, said the spokesman, adding that Iraq
will attend it and see what will result from the meeting
and accordingly it will outline its position.
</P>
<P>
He said this postponement is due to a demand by Saudi
Arabia whose foreign minister recently visited Cairo and met
Egyptian officials and the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
"Thus the secretary-general has subjected to the will of
one country for its obedience to the American influence and
this country is ready to implement what America asks for at
the expense of sovereignty and dignity," said the spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
