<HEADLINE> Pak Government's Bank Borrowing Exceeds Annual Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The total borrowing by the
Pakistani government in the first five months (July-November) of
the current fiscal year reached 75 billion rupees (1.63 billion
U.S. dollars) as against the annual budget target of 43 billion
rupees (934 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the State Bank of Pakistan (SBP) Tuesday
after its Central Board meeting held here in the morning.
</P>
<P>
"Drying up of foreign inflows and inadequate revenue
performance were the two main factors responsible for excessive
government borrowing for budgetary support," said a statement by
the SBP.
</P>
<P>
However, the monetary impact of the borrowing was much less
because nearly 34 billion rupees (739 million dollars) of the
borrowing was kept as deposits with the SBP, representing rupee
counterpart of foreign public debt that could not be paid due to
foreign exchange constraint, it said.
</P>
<P>
The SBP said that the monetary impact of borrowing for
budgetary support of the accumulated deposits for debt payments,
was of 41 billion rupees (891 million dollars) only, which was
within the target for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
In context of anticipated normalization of relations with
international financial organizations and inflow of external
resources, the Board approved a revised Credit Plan for 1998-99
fiscal year that envisages monetary expansion of only 9.2 percent
as compared with the original target of 13.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting noted that the lowering of the target for monetary
expansion is entirely due to the anticipated contractionary impact
of the government sector.
</P>
<P>
Credit to the private sector will remain protected as
originally approved and in addition foreign sector is expected to
become expansionary due to anticipated accumulation of net foreign
assets.
</P>
<P>
The Board, however, underscored the importance of prudence in
lending to the private sector by the financial institutions to
protect the depositors' interest and health of the banking
institutions and in this regard hoped that the lending process
will continue to remain "depoliticized". 
</P>
</TEXT>
