<HEADLINE> China Banks Ready for Euro-Related Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Most of China's major
commercial banks have declared themselves ready for euro-related
banking services, with only two days left before the final
launching of the new unified currency for the 11 European Union
nations -- the euro.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of China (BOC), the nation's leading foreign exchange
bank, said its five branches in relevant EU countries will be
capable of providing all euro-related services beginning next
year, just the same as any large European bank.
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt branch of the BOC will be the sole settlement
center for the bank itself, as well as for all the other banks in
China, since it is the only Chinese bank which has networked its
settlement system with TARGET, the transnational settlement system
of the European central bank.
</P>
<P>
The BOC will start euro-related services such as deposits,
remittance, foreign exchange buying and selling, and selling and
acceptance of traveler's check in euros for individual clients in
China. And companies in China will have access to all
euro-related services including the opening of euro accounts,
settlements, deposits, loans, foreign exchange buying and selling,
traveler's checks, and hedge services against exchange-rate risks.
</P>
<P>
The bank is also expected to give daily exchange rates for the
yuan against the euro, interest rates for deposits and loans in
the euro, and the rate of the euro against the currencies of the
11 EU nations.
</P>
<P>
The China Construction Bank, one of the big four state-owned
commercial banks, said it will start to accept deposits in euros
as well as in the currencies of the 11 EU nations beginning on
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China also pledged to
provide euro-related services including the opening of euro
accounts, foreign exchange remittance in euros, buying and selling
of euros, and traveler's checks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
