<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Approves Date for Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Tuesday approved May 17, 1999 as the date for the early elections
of a new Knesset and a new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
It also decided that a second round of voting for prime
minister will take place on June 1, if no candidate gets 50
percent votes in the first round.
</P>
<P>
The date for the early elections was agreed upon by both
ruling Likud Party and opposition Labor Party Monday after
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
With the date for the early elections having been approved by
the Knesset, the bill calling for dissolution of the existing
Knesset for early elections will be subjected to a second and a
third reading in the Knesset plenum next week.
</P>
<P>
Since some Knesset members of the Likud also joined the
opposition to vote for the bill in the first reading early this
month, the bill is expected to become legislation without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has kicked
off his campaign for reelection.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Netanyahu visited and prayed at the Western Wall
in Jerusalem, a remnant of the Second Temple and Judaism's
holiest site. According to the Jewish calendar, Tuesday is the
first day to memorize the destruction of the temple by the Roman
legion.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Netanyahu reiterated that Jerusalem is the
indivisible capital of Israel. But the Palestinians have claimed
that they will set up their future independent state with
east Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Local media said that Netanyahu will use his insistence on
Jerusalem affair to get more support in the pending elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
