<HEADLINE> Philippines Industry Output Down in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Weak market and economic
slowdown pulled down the volume of industry production of the
Philippines by 15.9 percent in October from a year earlier, the
National Statistics Office of the Philippines said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Value of industry production decreased year-on-year by 8.0
percent in October this year while industry sales volume and value
dropped by 12.8 percent and 5.0 percent respectively, the office
said in its monthly survey on selected industries.
</P>
<P>
The drop in production was largely attributed to the declines
in petroleum products, basic metals and transport equipment during
the period, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum products posted year-on-year decreases of 18.7
percent in volume and 20.5 percent in value of production.
</P>
<P>
Due to prevalent weak demand, the basic metal sector declined
by 46.0 percent in volume and 44.8 percent in value of production
in October from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Transport equipment fell year-on-year by 38.5 percent in volume
and 26.2 percent in value of production, which could be attributed
to the economic slowdown during the period.
</P>
<P>
Gainers in both volume and value of production were the paper
and paper products and wood and wood products in October this
year, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics of the office also showed that 41.8 percent of the
surveyed plants operated below 70 percent of capacity, ratio of
output to the maximum capacity of a plant, in October 1998
compared with the 31.5 percent in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 15.0 percent of the sample firms operated at full
capacity, 90 percent to 100 percent of the maximum capacity, in
October this year, compared with the 18.1 percent the same period
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
