<HEADLINE> EDS-Updated with Reports from Shanghai China Adopts First Securities Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislative body,
adopted the nation's first Securities Law today with 135 approvals,
three abstentions and no objections.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin signed a presidential
proclamation which lists the effective date of the law as July 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
"The law outlines fundamental principles for codes of conduct
governing the country's securities market," according to Li Peng,
chairman of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
"It will play an important role in pooling construction funds,
protecting the legitimate rights and interests of investors,
preventing and resolving financial risk and guaranteeing the
healthy development of China's fledgling securities market," said
Li.
</P>
<P>
The chairman noted that legislators formulating the law drew
lessons from the Asian financial crisis and China's experiences
during development of the speculative industry.
</P>
<P>
"The diligent work has effectively enhanced the capacity of the
law to prevent a market crisis and guaranteed the feasibility of
China's market operations," said Li.
</P>
<P>
"Passing the law was far from an easy task," according to Li
Yining, a renowned Chinese economist and chief author of the law.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Li acknowledged the five-week slide on China's major
stock markets in Shanghai and Shenzhen and said the fact that the
promulgation of "the Securities Law will standardize and regulate
the immature market will be 'good news' for investors."
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that promulgation of the law has forced
speculators engaged in activities strictly prohibited by the
rigorous stipulations in the new law to withdraw funds. They also
pointed the withdrawal of funds as one reason for the prolonged
drop in market indexes.
</P>
<P>
The law will help promote sound and healthy markets and overall
economic prosperity which will in turn benefit the stock market,
said Li. He also urged investors to exhibit greater confidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
