<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislature Has Full Work Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese law makers are
expected to have a full work schedule during the next four years,
with nearly 90 laws waiting to be drafted.
</P>
<P>
According to the legislation plan of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress, the committee will finish drafting
63 laws and regulations and complete research work on another 26
before the committee's term of office expires in the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
Laws of primary importance that require imminent drafting
include legislative and supervision laws, the law on the
organization of the State Council, a dozen business laws
concerning contracts and administration, and laws related to civil
servants and air-pollution prevention.
</P>
<P>
Major economic laws dealing with telecommunications, taxation
and individual income will also be high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Most sensitive and prominent may be the draft of laws
concerning the press, publications and association, which require
a depth of research, according to Li Peng, chairman of the NPC
Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The chairman urged lawmakers to conduct extensive
investigations and research before working on the new draft laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
