<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO/WFP Report Predicts Near-Record Crops in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A joint report issued
here Tuesday by the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) and the World Food Program (WFP) predicts that
Ethiopia will harvest 11.69 million tons of cereal and pulse this
year.
</P>
<P>
The predicted harvest will be a 36-percent increase than that
of last year, but slightly less than the record crops of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The press release quoted the FAO/WFP Crop and Food Supply
Assessment Mission to Ethiopia as attributing the better crop
yields this year to a favorable rainy season, increased use of
fertilizers, improved seeds and few occurrences of crop diseases
or pests.
</P>
<P>
However, said the mission, in some parts of the country,
excessive rains cut short the planting season, flooded fields,
damaged the barley and pulse crops and increased weed
infestation.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia will have surplus crops available for export, said
the mission, adding that grain could be exported to Somalia,
which suffered an estimated 125,000 tons deficit this year.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the expected excellent harvest in the
country, the mission said some two million people will still
require 180,000 tons of food aid in 1999.
</P>
<P>
While the FAO/WFP mission estimated that only some four
percent of the rural population will require food aid in 1999,
approximately 26 million Ethiopians, or more than 40 percent of
the farming population, do not produce enough food or income to
meet their families' basic nutritional requirements.
</P>
<P>
About half the population of Ethiopia lives below the poverty
line, said the press release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
