<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's GDP Falls by 7 Percent in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The expenditure-based gross
domestic product (GDP) of Hong Kong for the third quarter of 1998
is estimated to have fallen by 7.1 percent in real terms from a
year ago, following a decline of 5.1 percent in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released Tuesday by the Census and
Statistics Department of Hong Kong, the preliminary GDP estimate
for the third quarter matches closely with the crude initial
assessment made by the government in late November, which
indicated a decline of around 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Overall inflation in the economy, however, in terms of the
implicit price deflator of GDP, moderated distinctly further, to
only a 0.4-percent rise in the third quarter over a year earlier,
from increases of 4.5 percent in the first quarter and 1.9 percent
in the second.
</P>
<P>
The large decline in GDP in the third quarter of this year was
mainly due to the continued slackening in local consumer demand, a
significant decline in investment spending and a further setback
in export performance.
</P>
<P>
Putting the major GDP components on a year-on-year comparison,
private consumption expenditure continued to contract, by 10
percent in real terms in the third quarter, following a
5.1-percent drop in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Local consumer spending during the quarter was depressed by the
continued rise in unemployment and a further dip in asset prices.
But also relevant was the particularly high base of comparison in
the third quarter of last year, when private consumption
expenditure grew by 11.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Government consumption expenditure in national account terms
increased by 3.7 percent in real terms in the third quarter,
having dropped by 5.3 percent in the second.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic fixed capital formation decreased by 9.1 percent
in real terms in the third quarter of 1998, after an increase of
5.6 percent in the second quarter. This significant downturn was
mainly attributable to a marked decline of 10.8 percent in real
terms in overall expenditure on building and construction in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
On visible trade, total exports of goods fell by 7 percent in
real terms in the third quarter, further down from the 0.5-percent
decrease in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Imports of goods fell even more markedly, by 10.5 percent in
real terms in the third quarter, on account of the setback in
domestic demand and further decline in re-exports. This followed a
1.8-percent decline in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
On invisible trade, exports of services recorded a more
moderate decline of 3.7 percent in real terms in the third
quarter. The improvement from the 11-percent decline in the second
quarter was mainly due to the pick-up in inbound tourism in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, imports of services slackened to a
1.2-percent decline in real terms in the third quarter, mainly due
to the setback in imports of transport and financial services and
slower growth in spending by Hong Kong residents in outbound
trips.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman commented that the marked
downturn in exports of goods depressed overall economic
performance in the third quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Also equally relevant was the fact that the sharp volatilities
and price falls in the financial markets during the quarter,
continued credit stringency, high interest cost and uncertain
economic outlook all severely hit domestic demand, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Yet the spokesman observed that there were certain positive
signs emerging more recently, including improved liquidity from
the earlier tight situation, successive cuts in local interest
rates and a rebound in share prices and housing prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
