<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has
attracted investments of over 5 billion U.S. dollars since it was
established in 1996, said Jamil Harara, Director of the Investment
Department at the Palestinian Ministry of Finance Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 3 billion dollars have been used to finance the
banking and financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said the PNA issued investment laws in 1998 that meets the
requirements of Palestinian economy and will guarantee investments
in the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian "Royal Wings" company will increase its
flights in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Weekly flights between Amman and Aqaba will increase from the
current one flight to 14. And the Amman to Tel Aviv flights will
increase from six to eight, Amman to Gaza up to three from the
present two flights. However, flights between Amman and Haifa will
remain at two flights a week as usual.
</P>
<P>
Company data show the number of passengers travelling between
Aqaba and Tel Aviv in 1998 stood at some 75,000 as compared to
some 21,000 travelers in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen's exports volume stood at 1.8 billion rials (13
million U.S. dollars) during the period from January to November,
an increase of 400 million rials (2.9 million dollars) over the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total value of re-exports during the same
period stand at 900 million rials (6.4 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Fish tops the list of exports, which includes salt, honey and
cotton, whereas, re-exports include gum, incense, coffee, and iron
materials.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- The European Union is considering providing Algeria
95 million European currency units (ECUs) (111 million
U.S. dollars) to finance the country's industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
Some 38 million ECUs, or 44 million dollars, will be used to
finance the restructuring of certain industrial projects in
Algeria. And 57 million ECUs, or 67 million dollars will be
allocated to bolster small and medium-size companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
