<HEADLINE> China's Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China has listed the increase
of farmers' income and rural stability as high priorities on next
year's rural work agenda, according to Minister of Agriculture
Chen Yaobang.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ongoing working conference on agriculture today,
Chen said the slowdown in the increase of farmers income has
become a problem hindering rural economic development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the per capita net income for farmers this
year is expected to increase by 3.3 percent, 1.3 percentage points
lower than last year's.
</P>
<P>
Chen attributed the slowdown to the oversupply of certain farm
products, ailing rural enterprises, and last summer's devastating
floods.
</P>
<P>
Chen also noted that rural stability is of great importance for
the social stability in China, and urged agricultural departments
to spare no effort in helping farmers solve problems and putting
government policies into effect, especially those on extending the
terms of farmland contracts and eliminating irrational burdens on
farmers. 
</P>
