<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: SAARC Lays Solid Foundation for Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) has made considerable progress in
many areas in the past 13 years, laying a solid foundation for
ongoing and future cooperation, outgoing SAARC Secretary-General
Naeem U. Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
He said the seven-nation regional grouping, formed in December
1985 to promote economic and social development in the region, has
made very significant achievements in three sectors - social
welfare, poverty alleviation and people-to-people contact.
</P>
<P>
SARRC has a very strong program in the social sector for
women's development, child issues and health and nutrition, Hasan
told Xinhua Monday in an interview at the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
SARRC has made a major contribution not only regionally but
also globally in this field because it has been cooperating very
closely with the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and other
United Nations agencies, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said cooperation in the area of poverty alleviation has
succeeded in increasing the life expectancy and decreasing the
female and child mortality in the region, as shown by the social
indicators of the member states.
</P>
<P>
"We're having better quality of life, not only in the urban
areas but also in the rural areas," said Hasan, whose three-year
term expires at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
He said this is to some extent the result of the cooperation
among the group's member states through common programs as well as
their national development efforts.
</P>
<P>
SAARC has succeeded as well in having more people-to-people
contact in the region, through which it is able to promote
understanding and goodwill among the peoples, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These are three very significant achievements of SAARC," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
In the international arena, SAARC has established contact and
cooperation with U.N. agencies and other like-minded regional
groupings like the European Union and the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We have started adopting common positions on important
economic and social issues including WTO (World Trade
Organization) negotiations in Geneva," he said. "I think this is a
very important development because it strengthens our hands to
deal with the rest of the regional groupings."
</P>
<P>
"I think these have laid a very solid foundation for our
ongoing and future cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He identified more direct involvement of the private sector and
non- governmental organizations, growing interactions with other
regional groupings, increasing coordination of positions on
important issues and increased economic cooperation as the major
features of the grouping during his three-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
"I was fortunate to come at a time when SAARC was moving from
symbolic and general cooperation to specific areas of activities,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
During his tenure, the agreement on the SAARC Preferential
Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) went into operation and negotiations
under the SAPTA started.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of trade negotiations have been completed under
the SAPTA operational since December 1995, offering over 5,700
items of products for preferential entry among the SAARC member
states -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan
and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"So I would say increased economic and trade contact and
cooperation have been one of the major features of the last three
years," Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has not got the latest figure about the
intra-SAARC trade which, one year ago, accounted for a meager 3
percent of the region's total foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
"But certainly, whatever information we're receiving, there is
no doubt that trade among the member countries is definitely
increasing," he said. "In some cases it is almost doubled in the
last two years, for example between Bangladesh and India, between
Sri Lanka and India."
</P>
<P>
"Definitely all our efforts are having effect on increasing
trade. But of course, we have to do more because we want to raise
the volume by up to 10-15 percent in the next 5-10 years," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the fourth round of trade talks under the
SAPTA will start early next year after the meeting of SAARC
commerce ministers in early February in Dhaka of Bangladesh and
that of the foreign ministers later that month in Colombo, Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
He said there has been no decision on a deadline for the
realization of a South Asian Free Trade Area. Even at the summit
in Male, the Maldives, in May 1997, there was no definite decision
but only a feeling that SAARC should try to set up a free trade
area as early as possible and preferably by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The 10th SAARC summit held in Colombo in July this year agreed
that a comprehensive treaty regime for creating a free trade area
should be drafted by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Hasan said that a group has been set up for drafting the treaty
and it will start work early next year.
</P>
<P>
On the challenges facing the grouping in the next century, he
said that based on past experience, a greater interaction among
the member states is needed in the economic and trade field
because it is a global trend.
</P>
<P>
"We have to prepare ourselves for dealing with other trade
blocs as a group," he said. "This is what we're trying to
achieve."
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, I think we'll have to respond to the globalization
which is overtaking the whole world very rapidly," he observed.
"It also means we'll have to develop information technology
because the information revolution has totally changed our lives."
</P>
<P>
"I think we'll have to increasingly coordinate our positions as
we're starting doing on global issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that SAARC would also have to focus on environment
issues because the environment in the region is deteriorating
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan in
May this year have had any impact on the SAARC process, Hasan said
the tests were taken just before the 10th SAARC summit and there
was a lot of speculation.
</P>
<P>
But the summit took place on time and made some major
initiatives and some very substantial decisions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"So I think the SAARC process will continue and continue to
expand and strengthen, I hope, in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that bilateral relations between the
member states will develop further. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
