<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Introduces Reforms in 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
introduce innovations in the 1999 national budget to ensure
disbursement efficiency and improve monitoring, Benjamin Diokno,
secretary of budget and management, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Diokno told reporters that with the reforms, his department
will allow agencies to spend directly based on the 1999 General
Appropriations Act instead of having to obtain a General Allotment
Release Order.
</P>
<P>
With the simplification of the budget release procedure, the
department will be able to improve its capacity to monitor
agencies performances, he added.
</P>
<P>
The department will release funds in cash on a quarterly basis
instead of releasing funds on a monthly basis, to speed up the
implementation of projects.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was approved by Congress this month, will be
signed into law by Philippine President Joseph Estrada Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Estrada administration expects to limit the
budget deficit to 68 billion pesos (1.7 billion U.S. dollars),
about 2.2 percent of the projected Gross National Product (GNP)
for 1999, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
