<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Introduces New Kidney Transplant Procedure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Australian transplant
specialists have been successful in the past few months using a
new procedure to remove a kidney from its donor, which cuts down
on pain, scarring and recovery time.
</P>
<P>
Mohan Rao, a kidney transplant surgeon at Queen Elizabeth
Hospital in the south Australian port city of Adelaide, said
Tuesday that kidney donors in Australia would increasingly demand
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
Rao told the Australian Associated Press (AAP) that using
smaller incisions and removing the kidney from the donor's
abdominal cavity rather than the side of the body, was less
painful and allowed quicker recovery.
</P>
<P>
Rao said donors who had a kidney removed by the newer method
could leave hospital within three days instead of having to stay
for at least six days and could return to work sooner.
</P>
<P>
And the technique is cosmetically better, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are the only center that is offering it in this country,"
he told AAP.
</P>
<P>
Under the old way of performing kidney transplants, surgeons
made a longer cut through the muscle wall along the side of the
body.
</P>
<P>
Now, the operation is performed through small "keyhole"
incisions in the abdomen and a smaller, five-centimeter-long cut
is made at the front low on the left side of the abdomen through
which the kidney is removed.
</P>
<P>
"Traditionally we cut through the muscle wall to get to the
kidney. It's a long incision, it cuts through all muscles anywhere
up to 12 centimeters long," Rao said.
</P>
<P>
The hospital began using the technique in May last year and had
performed 30 transplants, all of which were successful, Rao said.
</P>
<P>
The hospital was this week recognized for the work as joint
winners of the south Australia state award for health.
</P>
<P>
Rao said surgeons in the United States began using the
technique first, six to 12 months before the Queen Elizabeth
Hospital, and he expected it to spread worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
