<HEADLINE> Defecting Khmer Rouge Leaders Meet Cambodian Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Defecting Khmer Rouge
leaders Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea arrived here Tuesday with
their families, and met with Prime Minister Hun Sen in his Takhmau
residence.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Samphan told reporters at the Royal Phnom Penh Hotel
after the meeting that he is very happy to return to the capital.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Khieu has returned to the capital
since 1994, when the Khmer Rouge was outlawed by the royal
government.
</P>
<P>
Nuon Chea has not been in Phnom Penh since the toppling of the
Khmer Rouge regime in 1979, when Vietnamese forces invaded and
drove the movement into its jungle bases.
</P>
<P>
When asked about their return to the society, Khieu said, "Our
return is for the peace and stability of the country. It is for
the national reconciliation and the unity of the nation."
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Hun Sen told us we should forget the past. Only
peace can build our country," Khieu added.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that their return marked the end of the Khmer Rouge
and not the beginning of a new Khmer Rouge as someone has
suspected.
</P>
<P>
The two Khmer Rouge leaders and their families will be tightly
protected by government security forces during their stay in Phnom
Penh. Accompanying them is Ieng Sary, who defected to the
government in 1996 and now controls a semi-autonomous zone in the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen approved Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea's defection to the
government on Friday, which was also supported by King Norodom
Sihanouk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
