<HEADLINE> Vietnam Bans Cement Joint Ventures in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has issued a ban on
cement joint ventures, according to the latest issue of the
Vietnam Investment Review.
</P>
<P>
The ban was announced in a five-year moratorium on new
Vietnamese/ foreign joint ventures in the cement industry by the
Vietnam Cement Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following warnings from the domestic
cement industry that a locally-produced glut, combined with cheap
illegal imports, could force hundreds of Vietnamese cement firms
out of business.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies have invested over a billion U.S. dollars in
cement joint ventures in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The joint ventures now produce 5.4 million tons of cement
annually and Vietnam's domestic demand for cement stands at 11.6
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Attempts by domestic companies and foreign-backed companies to
meet this demand are being thwarted by unlawful imports, priced as
low as 30 dollars per ton, the weekly said.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam-based plants' price usually hover around 60 dollars
per ton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
