<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cut Proposed in Excise on Cars in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- India's Industry Ministry is
likely to recommend a steep cut in excise duty on passenger cars
from 40 percent to 25 percent in a bid to boost the sagging demand
for cars in the country, a government official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the government's proposed "bold fiscal
initiatives" to fight the deceleration in the economy by
generating more demand.
</P>
<P>
The government has recently announced some fiscal incentives by
allowing a 40-percent depreciation for commercial vehicles
purchased in the current fiscal year after October 1, 1998,
irrespective of the number of days for which the vehicles have
been used.
</P>
<P>
The increase in car sales is expected to compensate the
reduction in excise duty collection, Industry Ministry officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian domestic car industry has a capacity of 1 million
vehicles per annum, but it is operating at only half of its
capacity. The steady fall in sales is expected to further push
down capacity utilization. Several car manufacturers have already
effected steep cuts in their daily production, the same officials
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
