<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: HK to Remember Old Airport With New Garden (Part 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- If the year 1997 was
remembered by Hong Kong for the return of the territory to China
after some 150 years of colonial rule, the year 1998 can be easily
remembered for just one name -- Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people crowded the vicinity of the 73-year-old
Hong Kong International Airport at Kai Tak, Kowloon, to bid
farewell to their "old friend" prior to its closure in early July.
The scene was described by some as next only to the sensation
brought about by the British band Beatles in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Shooting pictures by all kinds of tools -- from snapshot camera
to digital equipment -- not only became a free entertainment for
Hong Kong residents but produced some retrospective exhibitions at
downtown shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
Kai Tak is now making new friends -- Pop diva Celine Dion is to
perform at Kai Tak on January 23, 1999, with "My Heart Will Go On"
and other top-chart tunes, marking the first-ever Asia tour of the
French Canadian singer.
</P>
<P>
And Kai Tak is no longer all about aviation. It will be given
new meanings and will take off into the new century with a brand
new look.
</P>
<P>
Plans have been drawn up to build a Garden City at the Kai Tak
airport site and adjacent areas to house more than 320,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious program, known as the South East Kowloon
Development (SEKD), is being speeded up to allow for the intake of
population to start in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The new city will be fully self-contained with world-class
amenities, schools and transport links to other urban districts.
It will involve 579 hectares of land of which 280 hectares will
come from the existing airport site and the rest from reclaimed
land.
</P>
<P>
The Garden City will have a 50-hectare Metro Park, a
world-class international sports stadium with a retractable roof,
an Aviation Academy and Museum, 45 schools, a hospital and office
buildings and malls, according to the plans announced in early
September.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the park will become the leisure and
recreational node for the whole area, attracting not just people
from all over Hong Kong, but international tourists and athletes.
</P>
<P>
More than 14,000 jobs will be created during the reclamation
and construction period which is expected to span more than 10
years. Site formation will start at the end of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
