<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK People's Rights, Interests Fully Protected(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong remains free and
open and its residents' legitimate rights and interests are fully
protected under the Basic Law after its return to China on July 1
last year.
</P>
<P>
This conclusion has been proven by a public opinion survey
conducted by the Chinese University of Hong Kong in December this
year.
</P>
<P>
Among 788 respondents aged between 18 and 40, about 80 percent
said they were satisfied with a high degree of freedom in Hong
Kong and 60 percent expressed satisfaction with the present Hong
Kong's human rights situation.
</P>
<P>
About 72 percent of respondents held that freedom of speech
that the Hong Kong people enjoy has been well ensured and 88
percent agreed that freedom of traveling to and from Hong Kong has
been fully guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 percent said that the Hong Kong people enjoy freedom
of association, of assembly, and of precession and demonstration.
</P>
<P>
As Elsie Leung, secretary for Justice, has said that after Hong
Kong's return to China, the SAR government has been doing all it
can under the Basic Law, through administrative and legal means,
to further enhance the protection of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The fact is that provisions of the six significant human rights
conventions as applied to Hong Kong continue to have force in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
These cover a wide range of subjects such as guaranteeing civil
and political rights, economic, social and cultural rights, the
rights of child, and eliminating all forms of racial
discrimination and all forms of discrimination against women.
</P>
<P>
During the May Legislative Council election, the first of its
kind since the HKSAR was established on July 1 last year, a record
number of 1.49 million Hong Kong residents, or 53.3 percent of the
2.8 million registered voters, turned out to vote against heavy
rains.
</P>
<P>
Their broad and active participation in the election was
unprecedented in Hong Kong's history. During the 1995 Legislative
Council election under the rule of the British Hong Kong
government, the overall turnout rate was only 35.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is a demonstration of Hong Kong people's enthusiasm to
exercise their civic rights and of their determination and
confidence in "one country, two systems" and Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong with a high degree of autonomy, said David
Lan, secretary for Home Affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: HK to Remember Old Airport With New Garden (Part 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Garden City is just one of the many major infrastructure
projects the SAR government has planned for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Public works at the site are estimated to cost the government
some 36 billion HK dollars (4.6 billion U.S. dollars), but sales
of the land at the site is expected to total 160 billion HK
dollars (20.5 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Like the state-of-the-art new airport at Chek Lap Kok, the SAR
government is fully committed to the implementation of the program
as it is vital for the continued economic growth of the territory,
says Donald Tong, director of the Hong Kong Economic and Trade
Office.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the new city, the Executive Council of the SAR has
just given approval for the planning and construction of the
territory's second railway linking west Kowloon to northwest New
Territories.
</P>
<P>
The new railway, known as the West Rail, will complement the
current line running from urban Kowloon to the Hong Kong-mainland
border at Lo Wu.
</P>
<P>
The 30.5-kilometer, electrified and double-track West Rail will
create 13,000 jobs in the next few years, with 14 main civil
contracts being awarded by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
Other projects include a 12.5-kilometer extension of the Mass
Transit Railway System, new port development, highways, bridges
and public housing estates.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1970s Hong Kong has built several huge new towns but
never so close to an existing urban area. The city needs new towns
because its current population of 6.7 million will have grown to
over 8 million by the year 2011.
</P>
<P>
The SEKD is a very important project for Hong Kong's
development in the 21st century, transforming the previous Kai Tak
Airport and the nearby Kowloon Bay area into a comprehensively
designed "city within a city," a government spokesman says.
</P>
<P>
This proposed project is the result of careful consideration
and thorough studies on engineering, economic and environmental
impacts and land uses, the spokesman says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
