<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK People's Rights, Interests Fully Protected (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong is proud of its track record on human rights. Like
what Lan has said that after Hong Kong's return to China, "we
have witnessed much more willingness on the part of our citizens
to exercise their rights."
</P>
<P>
From July 1, 1997 to November 30, 1998, there were some 2,700
public meetings and processions, averaging five a day, and some
1,299 societies were registered or exempted from registration
under the Societies Ordinance. So far the Police have not once
objected to any applications to hold such activities.
</P>
<P>
Leung, who was in private practice for nearly 30 years, said it
is the Hong Kong residents' conscientious action to safeguard
their own rights and interests by using laws.
</P>
<P>
Last year, when the government slaughtered all chickens in
local farms and all poultry at wholesale markets in a bid to get
rid of the source of influenza, a H5N1 virus of bird flu, a
chicken sales manager brought a charge against the government in
court, asking the government for compensation.
</P>
<P>
Although he lost a lawsuit, it fully reflected an ordinary
citizen's law consciousness, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a variety of ethnic and cultural groups with
differing religious beliefs. Buddhists have been co-existed and
lived in good harmony with Taoists, Jews, Muslims, Christians,
Hindus and Sikhs.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China, the SAR government neither
imposes any restrictions on the Hong Kong residents' freedom of
religious beliefs, nor interferes in their internal affairs of the
religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong residents' religious activities have been held as
usual. Schools, hospitals and welfare institutions run by the
religious organizations have been operating normally.
</P>
<P>
All of these show that some dire predictions that the rights
and freedoms of Hong Kong residents are about to be curtailed
after its return to China are totally wrong.
</P>
<P>
The fact is that the last 18 months have clearly demonstrated
that the SAR government is fully committed to the protection of
human rights by observing closely the Basic Law, maintaining the
rule of law and the independence of the judiciary while the
Central People's government does not interfere in Hong Kong's own
affairs at all.
</P>
<P>
These lay a solid foundation for ensuring the full protection of
Hong Kong people's rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
As Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa has described that Hong Kong
remains a robust and lively community where people have no
hesitation in speaking their minds.
</P>
<P>
The government will continue to do everything it can to protect
and preserve people's rights, he pledged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Marginally Lower on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed
marginally lower on the Singapore Stock Market Tuesday as trading
was thin in quiet Christmas trading and ahead of the New Year
holidays.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) finished 2.82 points
down at 1,378.45.
</P>
<P>
The turnover was thin totaling 79.61 million units worth 97.64
million Singapore dollars (about 58.87 million U.S. dollars).
Rises led falls by 121 to 97 with 202 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was a 5.69-million parcel of KepTLDBS w00
which transacted at 0.57 Singapore dollars per share. KepTL w02
was the second most heavily traded stock with a volume of 4.65
million units done. CMTel was next with 3.78 million counters
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Elec&AMP;E led the ascent of the day with a rise of 25 cents to
finish at 5.3 U.S. dollars. UOB went up 20 cents to close at 6.55
Singapore dollars. SemMarLog was up 19 cents to end at 2.33
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 led the descent of the day
slashing 100 cents to close at 22.3 Singapore dollars. OUB F was
next sinking 25 cents to 6.95 Singapore dollars. DBS F and SPH
retreated 20 cents and ended at 14.9 and 17.6 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said seasonal holidays have thinned trading with many
overseas institutions already having closed their books for the
year.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that market also ignored the interest rate
reduction by the United Overseas Bank, which announced Monday to
cut its prime lending rate to 5.5 percent from 6 percent following
similar action by the other big four banks in the country.
</P>
<P>
UOB's smaller-than-expected cut in its prime lending rate has
failed to encourage players and led some market observers to
revise their 1999 targets for the prime lending rate to 5 percent
from below 5 percent for next year. 
</P>
