<HEADLINE> Philippines Army Ready to Stop Secession Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Armed Forces of the
Philippines is ready to resume operations against separatist rebel
groups if they threaten the country's sovereignty, Orlando
Mercado, secretary of defense of the Philippines, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"If anybody wants to secede, we have no choice but to put down
the rebels," Mercado said in a radio interview. "That is our
responsibility under the Constitution."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Philippine President Joseph Estrada flatly rejected a
demand by the Moro Islamic Liberation Front to establish an
independent Islamic state in the south as a precondition to
resuming its talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said that the country's 1987 Constitution decrees that
there is only one government and one Armed Forces of the
Philippines, and that its territory should remain undivided.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said, however, the Estrada administration is exhausting
all peaceful means to deal with the rebels even if this process
takes a long time to realize. 
</P>
