<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Communications Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Phase one of the Integrated
Communications Network has been completed in 12 states of Nigeria
with the system connected with Calabar, capital of Cross River
State last week.
</P>
<P>
With the system's connecting with Calabar, capital of Cross
River State last week, the Nigerian police force (NPF)
headquarters in various state capitals are fully integrated into
the sophisticated communications network, the Guardian newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The network is designed to enable the police force to transmit
voice and data between state capitals, and provide the NPF with
an independent Private Network Link nationwide.
</P>
<P>
When Phase two of the project is completed, the NPF can extend
its communications from the police headquarters to the area
command centers and then further down to the divisional police
offices via an independent private network link in all the 36
states in the country.
</P>
<P>
After the system fully commissioned, the state-to-state
message transmission will be achieved through Ultra High
Frequency and Very High Frequency while the communications within
a state command will be channeled through a Demand Assigned
Multiple Access.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the crime rate in the most populous African
country had been on the increase and the sophistication with
which criminals are executing their activities cannot be combated
squarely without a corresponding state-of-the-art facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Currency Demand Skyrockets in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign currency demand in
Vietnam "skyrockets," the Vietnam Investment Review reported in
its latest issue.
</P>
<P>
The English-language weekly said foreign-invested enterprises
in Vietnam are facing "tough times," because the country's
"shrinking foreign currency reserves account is unable to match
their growing need for hard currency to pay for imports and
loans."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's banking system sells over 500 million U.S. dollars
worth of foreign currencies to foreign-invested enterprises (FIEs)
every year, the weekly quoted a recent report submitted to the
prime minister by Vietnam's state bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that in 1998 as much as 800 million dollars in
</P>
<P>
foreign currencies was supplied to FIEs and it estimated that
the demand for foreign currencies will jump to 1 billion dollars
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The report said local banks "sometimes do not have enough hard
currencies to sell to FIEs, a dilemma which had severely affected
their production and overall business performance."
</P>
<P>
Another increasingly gloomy development is the growing need of
many FIEs for hard currencies to pay off their debts, the weekly
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the weekly, in 1997, 550 million dollars was
transferred out of Vietnam to pay FIEs' debts. In 1998, it was 790
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"In the coming years, there will be an imbalance because the
need of FIEs for hard currency will not be met by their earnings
from exports," said the report by Vietnam's state bank.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the coming years, disbursement of
foreign-invested capital might slow down, there might be a drop in
registered projects, overseas loans might be reduced due to the
regional crisis, and the country's exports might become less
competitive because of the devaluation of regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
"All these things will affect the supply of foreign currencies
for FIEs," the report concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
