<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Backs Down on Minimum Salary for Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
slashed the minimum salary of civil servants from 5,200 Naira (60
U.S. Dollars) per month approved in September to 3,000 Naira (35
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decision came following dwindling crude oil export
earnings resulted from sustained low oil prices in the
international market, Oyo State Administrator Amen Oyakhire said
in southwestern town of Ibandan Monday.
</P>
<P>
Oil export accounts for more than 80 percent of the budgetary
revenue of the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Oyakhire told local media that "5,200 Naira is no longer
tenable, what is now tenable is 3,000 Naira."
</P>
<P>
According to the state administrator, Nigeria's 1999 budget
will be based on nine Dollars per barrel, compared with 17
Dollars per barrel in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Press Secretary to the Head of State, Malam Haruna,
told reporters in Abuja Monday that the decision to slash the
minimum salary is to save the transition program.
</P>
<P>
"If you leave the salary increase as it is, it will be a
time-bomb for the new civilian regime because the fact is there
is simply no money to pay that kind of salary," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government announced the increase of minimum
monthly salary for federal civil servants from 600 Naira (seven
Dollars) to 5,200 Naira in September, sparking off a nationwide
labor unrest, as state governments insist that they do not have
the resources to pay the same salary to their own workers.
</P>
<P>
In fact, many federal civil servants have not been able to
receive their new salaries in the past months because the
governments do not have the money.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with This Day, a major national newspaper last
Friday, Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar
admitted that "we made a mistake in announcing that wage
increase."
</P>
<P>
He continued that "with the dwindling resources caused by the
fall in the price of crude oil, there is no way the federal
government can sustain that increase."
</P>
<P>
"Even if the federal government can afford to pay, since
states are not viable, we are going to put the states in a real
mess if we go ahead with the increase which may lead to further
unrest," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria will have its first elected civilian president in 15
years sworn in on May 29, 1999, according to the current military
administration's transition to civil rule program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
