<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Toyota Zambia has targeted to
win more than 50 percent of the country's motor dealer market
from which it hopes to take about 28 billion Kwacha (about 10
million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Tuesday quoted Toyota Zambia's Financial
Manager, Douglas Mc Crindle as saying that the company is also
in the process of establishing a dealer network throughout the
country to expand its business line.
</P>
<P>
"So far we are strengthening our overall performance so that
we claim about 54 percent of the local market, we wish to get
about 60 percent," said the manager in an recent interview with
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Crindle said the company has initiated a comprehensive program
which involves the provision of services to meet the ever
changing customer needs.
</P>
<P>
A number of local dealers will be engaged
across the country to market and sell the company's products
which are directly imported from Japan, he added.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, will also contribute to employment generation
in the areas where dealers will be appointed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company's sales manager, Malyombo Mumbi,
expressed confidence about the company's performance which, he
said, has been boosted by the modern fleet of vehicles that the
firm is dealing in.
</P>
<P>
According to Toyota Zambia Managing Director, Martin Grasett,
the company plans to invest about 14 million U.S. Dollars in
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The company is currently constructing a two million
Dollars ultra-modern showroom on Cairo Road in Lusaka, which is
expected to be ready by the second half of next year.
</P>
<P>
The facility will house a banking service outlet for leasing
transactions, insurance offices, repair shop, panel beating
sections and spare parts warehouse.
</P>
<P>
The company has also initiated a special package by which
customers can purchase vehicles on leasing terms through a
leasing agent but allowed to settle the costs in installments.
</P>
