<HEADLINE> Indonesian Tennis Player Urged to Dela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- New secretary-general of the
Indonesian Tennis Association (Pelti) Sugent Sarjadi has
suggested that the country's best ever tennis player Yayuk Basuki
delay her retirement for a year to give her prospective
successors more time to learn from her.
</P>
<P>
"I want to encourage her not to stop playing after the
Australian Open. Observing her convincing form in the Asiad, I
think it's too early for her to retire," Sugent was quoted by the
Jakarta Post Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yayuk reiterated her intention to leave competitive tennis
shortly after beating Thailand's Tamarine Tanasugarn to win the
Asain Games women's singles gold medal in Bangkok this month.
</P>
<P>
"I just want to settle down and enjoy the rest of my life with
my family. If God endows me babies, I'll be very happy because we
have long wished for them", said Yayuk, who married her coach
Suharyadi in January.
</P>
<P>
If the plan goes as expected, Yayuk will bid her farewell at
the Australian Open, which starts on January 18 next year.
</P>
<P>
"She's only 28, compared to Steffi Graf of Germany who is 29
and Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic who is 30. Neither have
plans to quit tennis in the near future," Sugent, who is also a
businessman, said.
</P>
<P>
Yayuk had twice dropped her retirement plan since 1996 ,
saying she could not evade the national duties laid on her
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
"I could do nothing but return to the tennis court that time
because I thought there was nobody to fill my shoes. Now that we
have a batch of young talents, there is no reason not to give the
young players a crack in international tournaments," Yayuk said.
</P>
<P>
Yayuk, who has collected more than one million U.S. dollars in
earnings from the tennis circuit and has donated 2.5 percent of
her income to the needy of Pelti.
</P>
<P>
Yayuk said she still had no idea about trying her hand at
coaching.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know if I want to have a tennis school or be a
coach. I don't know. All I want to do now is settle down," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
