<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
struggled back above the 61 U.S. cents mark Tuesday to close
higher, after an overnight battering that saw it sink to a
two-and-half-month low in offshore trading.
</P>
<P>
On the first trading day in Sydney since Christmas Eve, the
Australian currency finished at 61.08 U.S. cents after falling to
60.57 U.S. cents in the United States Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The local unit finished last Thursday at 61.03 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank treasury manager Nick Volanakis said the
overnight fall was related to concerns over commodity prices,
particularly gold and Tuesday's recovery was the result of an
exaggerated, thin market.
</P>
<P>
Generally weaker commodity prices and concerns over the impact
on gold prices of the January 1 euro currency introduction
resulted in the local unit hitting the early-October lows,
Volanakis said.
</P>
<P>
Trading was expected to continue quietly ahead of the New Year
holiday, with no domestic data due out this week.
</P>
<P>
At the local close the Australian dollar was trading at 70.55
Japanese yen from its Christmas Eve close of 70.52 yen and 1.0223
German marks from 1.0228 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
