<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Finish Higher in Subdued Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
finished higher Tuesday in subdued trading with the holiday season
in full swing.
</P>
<P>
The move on the local bourse mirrored a similar slight increase
on Wall Street overnight and barring any drastic events in the
United States, shares would continue to drift for the rest of the
week, Henderson Charlton Jones' Stuart Smith said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index lifted by 4.4 points to
2,768.4 points.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index gained 10.1 points to 4,982.1 while
the All Resources dropped 0.8 points to 955.9.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector strengthened by 28.1 points to 6,340.6.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank (NAB) and Westpac bank were both
gainers following media speculation that the two banks would be
the first to benefit from any fall in the Australian federal
government's four pillars policy that prevents mergers of the
country's four major banks.
</P>
<P>
NAB picked up 11.2 cents to 24.407 Australian dollars while
Westpac added 11.9 cents to 10.709 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia was also higher, gaining 18
cents to 22.68 Australian dollars while ANZ bank softened 6.6
cents to 10.5 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 190.87 million shares traded for 263.11
million U.S. dollars, with rising stocks outnumbering falling ones
by 387 to 347 and 323 stocks remaining steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
