<HEADLINE> (Quotes, Details Added) China Adopts First Securities Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislative body,
adopted the nation's first Securities Law today with 135 approvals,
three abstentions and no objections.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin signed a presidential
proclamation which lists the effective date of the law as July 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
"The law outlines fundamental principles for codes of conduct
governing the country's securities market," according to Li Peng,
chairman of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
"It will play an important role in pooling construction funds,
protecting the legitimate rights and interests of investors,
preventing and resolving financial risk and guaranteeing the
healthy development of China's fledgling securities market," said
Li.
</P>
<P>
The chairman noted that legislators formulating the law drew
lessons from the Asian financial crisis and China's experiences
during development of the speculative industry.
</P>
<P>
"The diligent work has effectively enhanced the capacity of the
law to prevent a market crisis and guaranteed the feasibility of
China's market operations," said Li.
</P>
<P>
"Passing the law was far from an easy task," according to Li
Yining, a renowned Chinese economist and chief author of the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts First Securities Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moreover, Li acknowledged the five-week slide on China's major
stock markets in Shanghai and Shenzhen and said the fact that
promulgation of "the Securities Law will standardize and regulate
the immature market will be 'good news' for investors."
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that promulgation of the law has forced
speculators engaged in activities strictly prohibited by the
rigorous stipulations in the new law to withdraw funds. They also
pointed the withdrawal of funds as one reason for the prolonged
drop in market indexes.
</P>
<P>
The law will help to promote sound healthy markets and overall
economic prosperity which will in turn benefit the stock market,
said Li. He also urged investors to exhibit greater confidence.
</P>
<P>
The law, which includes 214 articles in 12 chapters, covers
all aspects of the securities industry, ranging from the issuance
and trading of stocks to purchases of listed companies, stock
exchanges, securities brokerages, registration and account
settlements agencies, trading service agencies, self-disciplinary
associations, government regulatory bodies and penalties for
violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
The law clearly defines the three fundamental principles
governing the issuance of stocks as "openness, equity and
fairness." It also strictly prohibits fraud, insider trading and
market manipulation.
</P>
<P>
The Securities Law establishes a two-tiered system for the
securities industry. The system requires securities companies to
separate internal accounts from client accounts. Securities
transactions must also be clearly separated from banking, trust
and insurance operations, according to the law.
</P>
<P>
The State Council Securities Regulatory Commission is
empowered to exercise "unified" control over the securities market
and is held responsible for verifying the qualifications of listed
companies and approving stock issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts First Securities Law (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moreover, the law outlines detailed work procedures for
government regulatory bodies in order to curb corruption and
unfairness.
</P>
<P>
The new law eliminates sources for manipulating funds by
banning state-owned enterprises trading listed stocks and strictly
prohibiting bank funds from entering the market.
</P>
<P>
It also prohibits foreign capital from entering the A-share
market in order to protect domestic investors from the effects of
manipulation resulting from the actions of foreign money brokers.
</P>
<P>
"Investors must present legal documents proving their identity
and Chinese citizenship opening a stock account," according to the
law.
</P>
<P>
The State Council is currently deliberating regulations
governing Chinese stocks available to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Liabilities for violations of the law range from fines, to the
closure of businesses and criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the formulation of the securities law reflects
China's process in understanding rules governing the securities
market.
</P>
<P>
"Standards governing the market will continue to improve along
with the development of China's securities industry," according to
Li.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Securities Exchange, China's first stock exchange,
opened in 1990, with the value of the nation's stock markets
standing at 2,141.2 billion yuan by the end of June 1998. The
markets offer 811 listed companies and serve 37 million registered
investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
