<HEADLINE> Rwanda Refutes Report of Fighting With Ugandans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan army has
dismissed reports carried by a Ugandan newspaper that 30 of its
soldiers died in an exchange of fire with their Ugandan
counterparts deployed in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Ndahiro, Rwandan army spokesman, said Monday that
their forces did not clash with the Ugandan troops there although
they had some disagreements with Uganda over how to handle the
DRC war, the New Vision daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan army has no presence in northeastern DRC, in the towns
of Isiro, Beni and Buta where Uganda People's Defense Forces
(UPDF) is mainly based, Ndahiro added.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's daily newspaper Monitor reported Sunday that about 30
Rwandan soldiers and eight Ugandan UPDF men were killed when
Ugandan and Rwandan troops, deployed to fight alongside DRC
rebels there, turned on each other recently in Isiro and Beni.
</P>
<P>
Both Uganda and Rwanda have admitted that they deployed troops
in eastern DRC for the sake of their border security while DRC
President Laurent Kabila has accused the two countries of backing
the rebels fighting to oust him from office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
