<HEADLINE> China Deeply Disturbed by Exchange of Fire in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China is highly concerned
about the developments in Iraq and deeply disturbed by the
exchange of fire in northern Iraq and the casualties incurred.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao today when asked to comment on the exchange of fire
between the warplanes of the West and the anti-aircraft defenses
of Iraq in the No-Fly-Zone in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has maintained and made it clear on many
occasions that full respect should be given to the sovereignty,
territorial integrity and independence of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We hold that the establishment of the No-Fly-Zone inside Iraqi
territory runs counter to the U.N. Charter and norms governing
international relations," he said, and adding that "We call on
parties concerned to take necessary measures to avert further
deterioration of the situation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
