<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Sports Struggle to Survive Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A self-fulfilled medal
target at the Asian Games in Bangkok this month allowed
Indonesian sports to breathe a sigh of relief, at least for the
moment, the Jakarta Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that Indonesia's preparations for the
continent's major event were plagued by a hard-hitting recession
and security concerns, national athletes brought home six gold,
10 silver and 11 bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
An initial proposal suggested that the cash-strapped National
Sports Council (KONI) should take no more than 70 of the most
prospective medal-winning athletes to Bangkok. But as financial
aid poured in, and as the economic strain seemed to lessen, KONI
listed 128 sportsmen and sportswomen for the Games.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia had to wait a week after the Games opener on
December 6 for its first gold medal. Hendrawan led the new-look
national men's badminton team past archrival China 4-0, giving
Indonesia a back-to-back victory at the Asiad.
</P>
<P>
Of the five other Indonesian gold medalists, two came in as
unlikely winners. Underdog Supriati Sutono clinched the women's
5,000-meter title with a last-ditch sprint, and Arief Taufan
Syamsuddin, competing in the men's 60kg class, won gold while his
team expected to collect the laurels from woman's karateka
Nilawati Daud.
</P>
<P>
Supriati's glorious run ended Indonesia's 36-year wait for a
track and field gold medal at the Asiad. Mohammad Sarengat
earned the country two golds in 100 meters and 110 meters hurdles
at the 4th Asian Games here in 1962 .
</P>
<P>
The just-concluded Asian Games also marked a happy farewell
for Indonesia's tennis queen Yayuk Basuki. Smarting from a defeat
in the team event, Yayuk defied the odds to take the singles
crown. She beat the tournament's top two seeds in the process.
</P>
<P>
With Yayuk already setting a January date for her retirement,
Indonesia looks set to disappear from the world tennis map for a
while.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian badminton suffered a blow with a finding that
world men's doubles champion Sigit Budiarto failed a dope test in
the Singapore Open, which he won with Candra Wijaya in August.
</P>
<P>
Sigit, claiming that he unintentionally took nandrolone
anabolic steroids, was barred for one year by the International
Badminton Federation (IBF) following a hearing in November.
</P>
<P>
The punishment was 12 months lighter than the maximum
sentence for a player who violates the IBF anti-doping rules.
Sigit was the third Indonesian to be involved in a drug scandal
after men's singles Hastomo Arbi and in women's singles Minarti
Timur in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But badminton, again, salvaged Indonesia's pride this year
when in May, Hariyanto Arbi and companions stretched their Thomas
Cup men's team championship supremacy for the third consecutive
time.
</P>
<P>
Their female compatriots fell in the last hurdle at the hands
of star-studded China in Uber Cup.
</P>
<P>
Security uncertainty which preceded and succeeded the
transfer of power in May adversely affected sports activities in
the country. The Indonesian soccer league was the first to fall
victim when the national soccer federation prematurely stopped it
in May, leaving the tournament without a champion.
</P>
<P>
The federation's new chairman Agum Gumelar, who took over
from Azwar Anas, who resigned following the shameful behavior
during the Tiger Cup in August, reinstated the league on October
28 amid a sponsorship row.
</P>
<P>
In July, the Women's Tennis Association, the governing body
of women's professional tennis, cited security concerns for its
decision to drop two annual tournaments in the country.
</P>
<P>
Auto sports were another notable victim due to security
concerns. All events were sanctioned by the International
Automobile Federation (FIA). The FIA even failed to list the
used-to-be annual event in its calendar.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Grand Prix world motorcycling championships
was cancelled. Indonesia's Asian Omega Tour gold tournament also
missed the cut this year after its organizers fell short of funds
to provide the prize money.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesia Open badminton championships were lucky to
escape. The tournament suffered only a four-month delay from the
original schedule of July.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian shuttlers romped home with all but the men's
singles title. That prestigious crown went to Yong Hock Kin, the
first Malaysian ever to win a tournament on Indonesian soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
