<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Former Chief Minister Acquitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's former
Selangor State Chief Minister Muhammad Haji Muhammad Taib was
acquitted by the Kuala Lumpur High Court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Justice Abdul Wahab Patail made the ruling Tuesday morning
after hearing nine prosecution and seven defense witnesses over 11
days of hearing.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad, who is a vice president of the ruling United Malays
National Organization (UMNO), was charged for failing to declare
his and his family's assets.
</P>
<P>
But on June 10 last year, Muhammad pleaded not guilty to the
charge.
</P>
<P>
Justice Abdul Wahab said Muhammad's explanation for
non-declaration was that he believed that the properties had been
disposed of and he did not therefore own and have beneficial
interest and Muhammad's evidence of the disposal of beneficial
interest was corroborated with the evidence of transferring and
his evidence in court was unshaken in cross examination.
</P>
<P>
"So accordingly under Section 182 (A) (3) Criminal Procedure
Code, I accordingly order an acquittal on grounds that the
prosecution did not prove the case beyond reasonable doubt," he
ruled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
