<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Agriculture Improved Modestly in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural output in Kenya
is estimated to increase by 1.5 percent this year as compared
with 1.2 percent in 1997, the East African Standard newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The modest improvement stems from favorable weather conditions
that increased food crop production from the level of 1997 when
drought and El Nino-charged rains destroyed output, the Central
Bank of Kenya (CBK) said.
</P>
<P>
The cash crop sector continued to perform poorly due to lack
of affordable credit ad rising input costs. Structural
constraints to management and marketing have also contributed to
the sector's poor performance.
</P>
<P>
Arising from these factors, output of coffee and horticultural
products fell by 33 percent and 17 percent respectively in 1998
compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Coffee export earnings declined by 24.5 percent to 10.5
billion Shillings (about 175 million U.S. Dollars) for the period
between January to August compared with 230 million U.S. Dollars
over a similar period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, tea production and export earnings continued to
improve with average monthly production up by 30.8 percent to
24,121 tons from 18,442 tons in 1997 and export earnings to 400
million U.S. Dollars in the first nine months of this year, up by
69.5 percent over the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The less than satisfactory performance of the cash crop sector
is expected to persist through 1999, mainly because of the
falling prices of tea, coffee and horticultural crops, the CBK
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
