<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches Community Network to Help Aged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday launched
the Community Support Network (CSN) to help out the aged and the
disabled voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
The CSN aims to provide services to all levels of society that
need assistance, National Unity and Social Development Minister
Paduka Zaleha Ismail said at the launching in Petaling Jaya near
here.
</P>
<P>
The CSN will compile information about organizations offering
services, identify volunteers and refer those in need of
assistance to the relevant organizations or individuals, according
to the minister.
</P>
<P>
She said society needs to be aware of issues relating to the
aged and the appropriate care and attention they need.
</P>
<P>
The number of people aged above 60 is estimated at 1.2 million
out of Malaysia's population of 21 million.
</P>
<P>
There are about 2,000 aged people given shelter in old folks'
homes run by the Social Welfare Department and another 2,000 are
living in homes run by non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has declared 1999 as the Year of the Aged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
