<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Politicians Accused of Marring Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Political interference in
Zambia has marred the distribution of relief food in some parts
of the country, threatening to throw the whole exercise in
disarray, a charity body has warned here Monday.
</P>
<P>
World Vision Zambia (WVZ) Executive Assistant, Fred Simposya
said on Monday that a senior government officer last week tried
to force a WVZ worker in Choma of Southern province, to
accompany him to a political rally to refute claims that the
relief food was distributed by an oppositon party, and when the
the officer was refused, he threatened to halt the
distribution.
</P>
<P>
Simposya said in statement that politicians, eager to get
relief food to their areas as a campaign tool for the local
government elections to be held on December 30, have harassed WVZ
employees and even threatend to stop the distribution of the
relief food in some cases, the government-run newspaper, Times of
Zambia, reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Simposya noted that another politician demanded that WVZ
should move sorghum to his constituency from a warehouse
belonging to the Food Reserve Agency, but he was refused.
</P>
<P>
"While we understand that food is a political issue, there
should be some basic rules of decency and we appeal to the office
of the vice-president to ensure that politicians observe this to
safeguard the lives of our staff," he said.
</P>
<P>
Simposya said that as a non-partisan organization, the WVZ
would like to operate professionally instead of being drawn into
the political arena.
</P>
<P>
By November 30 this year, WVZ had distributed 33,281 bags of
25-kg mealie meal to Mpika, Gwember and Choma areas and another
200 bags of 50-kg rice to Kasama. the exericse is still going on
in other areas of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
