<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Obtains Big Loan From Foreign Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will get a
foreign currency loan of 1.35 billion U.S. dollars from foreign
banks operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government of Malaysia Tuesday signed a facility agreement
with a consortium of 12 foreign commercial banks incorporated in
the country for the extension of the five-year amortizing term
loan, available in U.S. dollars and Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Malaysian government will draw down
800 million dollars at the end of this year and the remaining 550
million dollars will be fully disbursed in early January 1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Malaysia's Second Finance
Minister Mustapa Mohamed appreciated the foreign banks for their
commitment to participating directly in Malaysia's economic
recovery process.
</P>
<P>
He said this smart partnership will be beneficial to not only
the country but also the foreign banks as an early economic
recovery provides a favorable business environment for all those
operating in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds from the loan will be utilized by the government
in its development program toward the economic recovery process
and to further strengthen the banking sector, Mustapa said.
</P>
<P>
He said the loan based on a market-driven rate, which carries
an all-in cost of 3 percent per annum, served as the benchmark for
the pricing of other foreign currency facilities to be raised by
the government and the private sector in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
