<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
agreed to award the civil servants a 25 percent cost of living
adjustment across the board, effective in January next year.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Joint Negotiation Council, Ignatius
Chigwendere said in a statement Monday that negotiations between
the government and staff association representatives had yielded
a 25 percent wage and salary increase.
</P>
<P>
The staff association representatives had hoped for a higher
percentage due to the constant and persistent erosion of their
incomes arising from pressure on the Zimbabwean Dollar, the daily
Herald reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"A 25 percent cost of living adjustment awarded for next year
goes a long way toward cushioning the civil servants' plight, but
does not go far enough in redressing present imbalances between
them and workers in industry in general," Chigwendere was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Public servants have been adversely affected by the current
economic situation like other Zimbabweans, he said, but they
believe their situation has been exacerbated by the fact they
are already at the bottom of the social structure.  
</P>
