<HEADLINE> RBI Report Rules Out 6 Percent GDP Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) has revised its outlook and said a growth rate of 6 percent
in gross domestic product (GDP) is clearly unattainable this year.
</P>
<P>
In its latest report, RBI has also termed the macroeconomic
situation as a matter of "serious concern." It has painted a
gloomy picture of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The increase in prices of primary commodities and the rate of
inflation has heightened uncertainty about output growth. RBI also
expressed concern about the high growth in money supply despite a
substantial increase in the cash reserve ratio and short-term
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"The slow growth in industry has clouded the prospect of
achieving a rate of growth of 6 percent, which was visualized at
the time of the mid-term review of credit policy in October 98,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report also stated that agricultural and industrial
performance has not shown indications of a strong recovery. Up to
October 1998, industrial growth turned out to be significantly
lower at 3.6 percent compared with 6.2 percent in the
corresponding period of the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
