<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spaniards Excited on Eve of Euro Launching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Spaniards are probably the
most excited in the 11 euro-area countries about entering the era
of euro, the single European currency to be launched on January
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government is really proud of its achievements in
meeting the five criteria outlined in the Maastricht Treaty for
joining the single European currency.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, the country was far behind in terms of any of
the five criteria including an inflation rate of below 3 percent
and a budget deficit lower than three percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP). But now in just two years, it is fully
qualified to become one of the first wave euro countries.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector also feels happy with its "most crucial and
irreplaceable" role in macro economic control in the past two
years, which has won applause from both the ruling and opposition
camps.
</P>
<P>
Spain's banking sector, as a matter of fact, has become the
most profitable banking sector in the entire Europe and it is
confident of its ability to compete with other banks in the
future euro market.
</P>
<P>
Business people in Spain have a much higher expectation in the
euro era as the labor force and raw material in the country are
cheap compared with other euro countries. They have been
encouraged to grasp the opportunities offered by the launching of
the single European currency to expand their businesses.
</P>
<P>
By joining euro, Spain achieved its long-held target of
integration with Europe, leaving behind the political alienation
which had been there since Francisco Franco Bahamonde was in
power.
</P>
<P>
The most excited in Spain are the young generation, who are
called the "euro generation." For them, all borders in Europe
vanished and they can travel freely and find jobs in any euro
country.
</P>
<P>
In the course to achieve the criteria set in the Maastricht
Treaty, Spain gained a steady economic development and the
inflation rate kept falling, a benefit many feel they gain in
advance from euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
