<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Deregister Over 300 Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 29 (Xinhua) - Tanzania will deregister
315 out of 425 newspapers due to their failure to start operation
within the stipulated period, the Tanzania Information Services
director said.
</P>
<P>
Kassim Mpenda told local media Monday that this will be the
government's first step in ensuring active performance of
registered newspapers in accordance with the Newspaper Act of
1976.
</P>
<P>
Mpenda said so far 425 papers have been registered in the
country but only 110 are presumably active on the market.
</P>
<P>
"Some papers have not been published ever since their
registration, such as the Daily Times, Bayana, Jambo and Harakati
as well as the Tanzania Law Magazine," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mpenda said that publishers of the newspapers will be given
three months, probably immediately after the New Year's Day, to
defend themselves before being deregistered.
</P>
<P>
He said the next step will be the evaluation of the
performance of all the 110 newspapers actually operating in the
market to be sorted out for another notice of deregistration.
</P>
<P>
However, the director did not specify the time set by the law
in which a paper should be on market after registration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
