<HEADLINE> China Set to Introduce New Investment Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) - China is set to introduce the
first in a group of five planned securities investment funds on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The closed-end Puhui Fund will carry a face value of one yuan
and will mature in 15 years. The issue is expected to raise total
capital of two billion yuan. The Penghua Funds Management
Co. Ltd. will manage the fund under the custodianship of the Bank
of Communications.
</P>
<P>
Introduction of the new fund indicates China's determination to
launch new investment funds to nurture institutional investors and
will promote the stability and standardization of the securities
market, according to an official with the China Securities
Regulatory Commission, the nation's securities watchdog.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that the current sluggish stock market
and weak performance of investment funds will not affect the
government's determination to introduce more funds.
</P>
<P>
Various funds are creating investment value in spite of sliding
prices over the past few months, and annual yields for some are
expected to exceed 10 percent when taking profits from new
subscribed stocks into account, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Investment funds emerged as star performers on the stock market
due to the introduction of favorable policies following the launch
of the first two funds -- Jintai Fund and Kaiyuan Fund -- in early
April.
</P>
<P>
Prices for said funds, in fact, surged above two yuan. However,
the failure of the funds to fullfill the expectations of investors
sparked a downward trend, with prices currently fluctuating at
around 1.2 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Prices for the funds have dropped to a reasonable level when
considering the sluggishness of the stock market. Funds will
continue to be a useful investment instrument for investors
seeking reasonable returns and low risk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
