<HEADLINE> Stern Wants NBA Vote, Union Says No </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- NBA commissioner David
Stern reiterated today the league's intension to cancel the
season while union director Billy Hunter said the union would not
vote on the owner's final proposal.
</P>
<P>
"I think the likelihood is the season will be canceled
January 7," said Stern, who is baffled by the union's strategy of
not voting on any of the proposals presented by the league.
</P>
<P>
"We're not inclined to take anything to membership for a
vote,"said Hunter, who continues to accuse NBA owners of engaging
in concession bargaining.
</P>
<P>
Stern and Hunter spoke in separate teleconferences less than
24 hours after the NBA declared it had made its final proposal at
a five-hour meeting in Denver. NBA deputy commissioner Russ
Granik added that the sides are "continents" apart.
</P>
<P>
"We do not anticipate any further negotiations between now
and January 7," Stern said. "If the players have something to
tell us, we'll take it back to our labor committee, but the
likelihood is that the season will be canceled on January 7."
</P>
<P>
Stern said the players negotiating committee will be blame if
there is no agreement by January 7.
</P>
<P>
Hunter still confident that a deal is possible, called for a
resumption of talks between both sides' negotiating committees.
</P>
<P>
"I'm convinced that if that does happen, there's a strong
possibility that an agreement could be reached," Hunter said.
"We've done everything that we believe is conceivable, and we
have been earnest in our efforts to make a deal. It comes down to
horse trading, and if they are inclined to trade further, we have
ample time to save the season."
</P>
<P>
"I believe our owners will vote overwhelmingly to reject the
players' last offer," Stern added.
</P>
<P>
The major difference appears to be a backup tax on the escrow
package that would be installed over the last three years of the
six-year proposal. The union believes there is no need for it,
while the owners want it as a financial security system.
</P>
<P>
The sides also are considerably apart on the percentage of
basketball-related income (BRI) to be allocated to the players
over the last three years. The league's final proposal called for
a raise of one percentage point in each year to 53 percent, 53.5
percent and 54 percent. The union is seeking 56 percent, 56 pe
rcent and 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
"They've got to do three things," Hunter said. "Give us a
number at or about 57 percent. They've got to give us the
exceptions we've asked for and they've asked for and they've got
to do away with the tax. I don't think it's necessary."
</P>
<P>
Hunter said 85 percent of his union is squarely behind him.
"I can't understand why you wouldn't allow the membership to
vote, but they tell us they don't have to," Granik said. "We were
instructed by our committee that this is as far as we can
possible go. They would prefer not to operate the NBA rather than
go any further than this proposal."
</P>
<P>
Stern said:"He didn't believe that the NLRB would dismiss the
unfair labor practice, and he didn't believe that Dean Feerick
would rule against him, and he didn't believe we'd lose
regular-season games, and he didn't believe we'd miss Christmas
Day, and he didn't believe we'd cancel the All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
"So his analysis of this has been right on target. And on
January 8, he'll turn to his players and say 'Guess what, I was
wrong.'"
</P>
<P>
Granik added:"Or maybe he'll say they didn't really mean it
if the owners cancel the season. But by then it will be too late
to make and difference."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
