<HEADLINE> Albania Passes Resolution Demanding NATO Intervention in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Albania's parliament on Monday
unanimously endorsed a resolution calling for NATO's intervention
in the Kosovo issue and the Albanian government's strong support
for ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Describing the current situation in Kosovo as extremely
grave, the resolution urged the international community, in
particular the United Nations, the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the United States, to participate more
actively and effectively in the process of seeking a political
solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under current circumstances, it is necessary for NATO to
intervene in the Kosovo issue to help find an early settlement to
the conflict and to avert humanitarian disasters there, the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
It also asked the Albanian government to give strong support
to "Kosovo brothers" , who, it said, are faced with an unusual
situation, in their efforts to seek autonomy in the Serb province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called for all political powers in Kosovo
and Albania to take a unified stand on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Albania's People's Assembly, or Parliament, originally decided
to vote on the resolution last Thursday, but had to postpone it
since deputies from the Democratic Party of Albania boycotted the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party of Albania, which did not attend Monday's
vote, had reportedly expressed its support for the resolution.
</P>
<P>
No comment is available now from the Yugoslav side.
</P>
</TEXT>
