<HEADLINE> Overseas-Funded Firms Contribute to Suzhou's Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded enterprises in
Suzhou, a scenic city of east China's Jiangsu Province, have
accounted for a constantly increasing portion of the city's fiscal
revenues in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded firms currently account for some 20 percent of
total fiscal revenues for the city which is located less than 100
km from Shanghai, China's largest economic and commercial center.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou has approved 7,560 overseas-funded enterprises since
1984, the second largest number of approvals in the Yangtze River
valley following Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,257 are currently in operation. Recent statistics also
show that 64 of the world's top 500 multinational corporations
have invested in the city.
</P>
<P>
The government decision to transform Shanghai's Pudong New Area
into a financial and trade center for East Asia has accelerated
the influx of overseas funds into Suzhou in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Contracted overseas investment averaged close to four billion
US dollars annually between 1992-1996, with the 1997 figure for
funds actually used hitting 2.4 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment mainly flows into the textile, light
industry, clothing, power generation and agriculture sectors,
according to a city government official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
