<HEADLINE> New Zealand-Asia Relations Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- "Asia will increasingly
shape our (New Zealand) future," Philli Gibson has said in an
article titled "Asia Will Be Back."
</P>
<P>
The article written by the executive director of the Asia 2000
Foundation of New Zealand was published Tuesday in the Dominion, a
 Wellington-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In the article, Gibson said Even with its economic downturn,
"Asia is still well ahead of where it was just a few years back."
</P>
<P>
"Asia's current problems need to be seen in the context of 30
years of extraordinary growth and development."
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand's engagement with the region similarly needs to be
put in context. Asia's downturn has affected us -- and in some
export sectors significantly so. But we remain way ahead of where
we were just a few years back."
</P>
<P>
Gibson noted that Asia at present takes around 35 percent of
New Zealand's total exports. That's down from 38 percent a year
ago. But it's still about the same as Europe and the United States
combined.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past 30 years, our (annual) exports to the region
have grown from around 150 million NZ dollars (78 Million U.S.
dollars) to nearly 8 billion NZ dollars (4.16 billion U.S.
dollars)."
</P>
<P>
"Even in recession, Asia remains vitally important to New
Zealand. It is the part of the world where we earn the most and
where we have the potential to earn much more."
</P>
<P>
The author stressed the importance of sustaining and developing
the friendships and relationships New Zealand has built in Asia,
having a keen eye for new trade and investment opportunities, and
knowing much more about the peoples, cultures and economies of
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Asia accounts for around one third of global gross domestic
product, contains over one half of the world's population and is
relatively close geographically.
</P>
<P>
"The reality is, Asia will increasingly shape our future," he
said in conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
