<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambia's Economy Experiencing Hard Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1998 saw Zambia's
economy experiencing a hard time following two successive years'
growth, which is characterized by less export earnings, slow
foreign investment, reduced purchasing power of people and heavy
burden of foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The real economic growth rate in the southern African country
is now estimated to be minus two percent this year from last
year's 3.5 percent and 5.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The growth target in the 1998 national budget was set at 5.5
percent and was revised to four percent at mid-year. However,
"many of the problems that emerged in the course of the year have
not been eased or resolved. As a result, the achievement of even
the revised macro-economic objectives for this year is not
possible," said Godfrey Simasiku, the country's Deputy Finance
Minister.
</P>
<P>
One of the major factors which stumbled the country's growth
pace is the drastic decline in export earnings. Total export
earnings for the year are expected to decrease to 888 million
U.S. Dollars from 1,159 million Dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings from Zambia's metal mining sector, the
country's major foreign exchange earner, dropped by 42 percent in
the first nine months of this year to 468.83 million Dollars from
809.3 million Dollars in the same period last year by official
count.
</P>
<P>
And copper earnings alone fell by 44 percent from 688.6
million Dollars realized between January and September last year
to mere 386.18 million Dollars in the same period of this year.
</P>
<P>
This is attributed to the economic crisis in Asia which has
reduced demand for copper thus dragging copper price further
down. Copper price dropped by 33 cents a pound in the London
metal exchange market to 77 cents in the first quarter of this
year compared with 110 cents in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Another factor which had adverse effect on the country's
economic growth this year is seen in less foreign direct
investment. According to World Investment Report 1998, Zambia
ranked the seventh from the bottom among the top 20 recipients of
foreign direct investment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
For Zambia, 1998 has seen a wait-and-see attitude from
investors. According to Lusaka Stock Exchange, though some
investors have invested in newly-privatized mines, investment
flows seemed to be merely trickling.
</P>
<P>
To make the situation worse, some donor countries withheld
their pledged aid of 530 million Dollars to Zambia this year in
excuse of the country not completing the privatization of its two
major copper mines.
</P>
<P>
Owing to lack of foreign exchange inflow, Zambia's central
bank had to pursue a tight monetary policy to withdraw excess
funds from the public to curb the speculative demand and
unnecessary demand pressures on the foreign exchange supply.
</P>
<P>
This policy, explained by the bank's spokesman Kabinga Pande,
also aimed to check the continuous depreciation of the local
currency Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
Kwacha has devalued drastically with 2,200 against one U.S.
Dollar at present, compared with 1,400 against one Dollar at the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
As Zambia is very dependent on imports, the depreciation of
Kwacha has pushed up the prices of imported commodities. The
prices of local products have also been hiked. As a result, the
purchasing power of Zambians, 70 percent of whom are living in
abject poverty, has been reduced.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the output of maize, staple food for Zambians,
dropped by 30 percent to only 650,000 tons this year compared
with that in 1997, which is lowest since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The output of soya, rice, sorghum and sunflower also fell due
to El Nino effects, necessitating substantial imports in the
final quarter and early next year, which will, in turn, have
adverse implications for both inflation and exchange rate of the
country's currency.
</P>
<P>
Further more, Zambia spent over 200 million Dollars in 1997 in
servicing its foreign debts now standing at seven billion
Dollars. This year the country is expected to spend 290 million
more on the debt servicing. The amount represents about one third
of its total export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Difficult as it was, Zambia's economy is hopeful in the long
run as seen by President Frederick Chiluba. He told a national
convention recently that the country should look away from
exclusive donor dependence in its economic development and tap
its resources to boost non-traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
"Our survival lies in the non-traditional sector, agriculture
in particular, which has the highest potential to support both
primary and secondary industries," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
