<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK People's Rights, Interests Fully Protected (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong remains free and
open and its residents' legitimate rights and interests are fully
protected under the Basic Law after its return to China on July 1
last year.
</P>
<P>
This conclusion has been proven by a public opinion survey
conducted by the Chinese University of Hong Kong in December this
year.
</P>
<P>
Among 788 respondents aged between 18 and 40, about 80 percent
said they were satisfied with a high degree of freedom in Hong
Kong and 60 percent expressed satisfaction with the present Hong
Kong's human rights situation.
</P>
<P>
About 72 percent of respondents held that freedom of speech
that the Hong Kong people enjoy has been well ensured and 88
percent agreed that freedom of traveling to and from Hong Kong has
been fully guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 percent said that the Hong Kong people enjoy freedom
of association, of assembly, and of precession and demonstration.
</P>
<P>
As Elsie Leung, secretary for Justice, has said that after Hong
Kong's return to China, the SAR government has been doing all it
can under the Basic Law, through administrative and legal means,
to further enhance the protection of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The fact is that provisions of the six significant human rights
conventions as applied to Hong Kong continue to have force in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
These cover a wide range of subjects such as guaranteeing civil
and political rights, economic, social and cultural rights, the
rights of child, and eliminating all forms of racial
discrimination and all forms of discrimination against women.
</P>
<P>
During the May Legislative Council election, the first of its
kind since the HKSAR was established on July 1 last year, a record
number of 1.49 million Hong Kong residents, or 53.3 percent of the
2.8 million registered voters, turned out to vote despite heavy
rains.
</P>
<P>
Their broad and active participation in the election was
unprecedented in Hong Kong's history. During the 1995 Legislative
Council election under the rule of the British Hong Kong
authorities, the overall turnout rate was only 35.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is a demonstration of Hong Kong people's enthusiasm to
exercise their civic rights and of their determination and
confidence in "one country, two systems" and Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong with a high degree of autonomy, said David
Lan, secretary for Home Affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK People's Rights, Interests Fully Protected  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong is proud of its track record on human rights. Like
what Lan has said that after Hong Kong's return to China, "we
have witnessed much more willingness on the part of our citizens
to exercise their rights."
</P>
<P>
From July 1, 1997 to November 30, 1998, there were some 2,700
public meetings and processions, averaging five a day, and some
1,299 societies were registered or exempted from registration
under the Societies Ordinance. So far, the police have not once
objected to any applications to hold such activities.
</P>
<P>
Leung, who was in private practice for nearly 30 years, said it
is the Hong Kong residents' conscientious action to safeguard
their own rights and interests by using laws.
</P>
<P>
Last year, when the government slaughtered all chickens on
local farms and all poultry on wholesale markets in a bid to
eliminate the source of influenza, a H5N1 virus of bird flu, a
chicken sales manager brought a charge against the government in
court, asking the government for compensation.
</P>
<P>
Although he lost a lawsuit, it fully reflected an ordinary
citizen's law consciousness, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a variety of ethnic and cultural groups with
differing religious beliefs. Buddhists have co-existed and lived
in harmony with Taoists, Jews, Muslims, Christians, Hindus and
Sikhs.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China, the SAR government neither
imposes any restrictions on the Hong Kong residents' freedom of
religious beliefs, nor interferes in their internal affairs of the
religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong residents' religious activities have been
conducted as usual. Schools, hospitals and welfare institutions
run by the religious organizations have been operating normally.
</P>
<P>
All of these show that some dire predictions that the rights
and freedoms of Hong Kong residents were about to be curtailed
after its return to China are totally groundless.
</P>
<P>
The fact is that the last 18 months have clearly demonstrated
that the SAR government is fully committed to the protection of
human rights by observing strictly the Basic Law, maintaining the
rule of law and the independence of the judiciary while the
Central People's government does not interfere in Hong Kong's own
affairs at all.
</P>
<P>
These have laid a solid foundation for ensuring the full
protection of Hong Kong people's rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
As Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa has stated that Hong Kong
remains a robust and lively community where people have no
hesitation in speaking their minds.
</P>
<P>
The government will continue to do everything it can to protect
and preserve people's rights, he pledged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Take up Heritage-Conserving Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
take up a 6-million U.S. dollar project next year to conserve and
develop the country's cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to be launched in the first
quarter of 1999, would be co-funded by the World Bank (WB), The
Daily Star, an English daily newspaper, reported Tuesday, quoting
official sources.
</P>
<P>
A proposal had been prepared for chalking out the details of
the plan by the Ministry of Culture Affairs which would work as
the executing agency of the project.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is likely to have negotiations with the WB in
January 1999 to get the green signal from the bank which will
provide 5 million dollars for the implementation of the project,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of monuments across the country would be one of
the main components of the project, and the other major components
of the project would include promotion of fine arts and
strengthening of public and private libraries, they stated.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is the second largest Muslim country in the world
with 86 percent of its 127 million people being Muslims, and
therefore, the Muslim cultural heritage in the country is rich,
which needs to be conserved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
