<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Sets 5 Conditions for Renouncing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Nationalist Party
(BNP), the major opposition in the parliament, has set five
conditions for renouncing hartal in response to the ruling Awami
League's non-hartal announcement made last November.
</P>
<P>
The conditions are: the government must "refrain from
repression on opposition," refrain from "anti-people and
anti-state activities," "ensure voting rights," "allow the
opposition to speak in parliament" and "create no obstacles to
street program of the opposition."
</P>
<P>
Begum Khaleda Zia, BNP chairperson and leader of the
opposition, announced the five conditions while exchanging views
with the newly elected executive body of the Federation of
Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industries here Monday, said
press reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina, prime minister and president of the ruling party
announced on November 15 that her party would "never call hartals"
either in power or in opposition in the future.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came in the wake of the three-day non-stop
hartal of the seven-party opposition alliance between November 9
and 11, which put the whole country at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
"I myself don't like hartal. We will not go for hartal if the
government adhered to the conditions," the BNP leader said, adding
"I believe that hartal sustains loss to the national economy."
</P>
<P>
The ruling party has made no reaction to BNP's five conditions
till now.
</P>
<P>
Hartal is a special political phenomenon in this South Asian
country. The opposition party often finds reasons to hold hartals
in opposing the ruling party, while the latter always adopts some
counter measures to control the situation. As a result, clashes
between the two sides often take place.
</P>
<P>
During hartals, all shops are closed, transport stops and
pedestrians are rarely seen in the street. Meanwhile, almost all
the economic activities in the capital and other major cities in
the country are at a standstill for a day or two days or even
more.
</P>
<P>
A day-long nation-wide hartal in the country may make the
national economy incur an estimated loss of 3.8 billion taka
(about 78.4 million U.S. dollars), according to the Finance
Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
