<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quarter-Century Step Toward Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The search for a Euro-dollar
currency has been a historic quest since the early 1970s when the
Bretton Woods system collapsed and the then six-nation European
Community (EC) started to look for a way to unite monetarily.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar has since been used by international financial
operators in western Europe. The dollar played its most
influential role in the 1950s and 60s. Now the present
15-country European Union (EU) is ready to enter into a new stage
of Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) after making a
quarter-century step toward the euro, the single currency that
was once just a dream for most political leaders in western
European nations.
</P>
<P>
When the world retraces the journey of the EMU, a serious
story will be told. When the United States allowed the dollar to
be floated in August 1971, a fresh wave of market instability
followed. By 1973, the energy crisis squashed the EC's hopes of
tying their currencies closer together. At that time, the EU
said, the then EC member states had not achieved a sufficient
degree of economic convergence and lacked the political will for
strong economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
However, this setback did not disrupt their interest in trying
to create currency stability. The European Monetary System was
launched in March 1979 with the initiative brought on by three
famous political figures: France's Giscard d'Estaing, West
Germany's Helmut Schmidt and Luxembourg's Pierre Werner. In the
meantime, all nine member states of the EC joined the system,
although the British pound remained outside the mechanism for
stabilizing exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the community gained success with the EMS.
Between 1979 and 1985, exchange rate variability was half what it
had been in 1975-79 and it halved again between 1986 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
In June 1988, the heads of EC member states at their Hanover
meeting set up the "Committee for the study of an Economic and
Monetary Union" under the chairmanship of the then President of
the European Commission, Jacques Delors. The committee included
all EC central bank governors and a few independent experts.
</P>
<P>
In April 1989, the committee members in their report
unanimously agreed that monetary union should be achieved in
three stages, moving from closer economic and monetary
coordination to a single currency and the European Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The report's recommendations shaped the EU Treaty signed in
February 1992 in the Netherlands' city of Maastricht city with
the objective of a single currency by January 1, 1999 at the
latest.
</P>
<P>
Based on the well-known Maastricht Treaty's three-stage
approach to the EMU, the union members tried to remove all
restrictions on capital movements and stepped up their efforts
for economic convergence. Capital movements had been freed in
most member states by the time the EU treaty came into force in
November 1993, a month before the end of the first stage.
</P>
<P>
In January 1994, the European Monetary Institute (EMI), the
forerunner of the European Central Bank (ECB), was set up and
given a number of preparatory tasks including surveillance
procedures introduced for promoting economic convergence.
</P>
<P>
During the second stage of EMU, which will end this year,
heads of the 15 EU members at their Madrid meeting in December
1995 established a definitive three-phase timetable and scenario
for the introduction of the single currency. They named the
future currency "the euro."
</P>
<P>
The third EMU stage will start on New Year's Day. According
to the EU treaty, the common basic law of the regional integr
ation bloc, the date of January 1, 1999, will see the launch of
the euro with the irrevocable locking of exchange rates between
the currencies of the nine countries in euro zone: Austria,
Belgium, Finland, France, Germany Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Portugal and Spain. At the same time, the ECB will
assume responsibility for monetary policy and exchange rate
policy.
</P>
<P>
Europe's dream will come true in just two days. Despite the
possibility of uncertain factors, such as "can the euro challenge
the dollar in the future," and "how long will the euro take to
become a hard currency," the European Union's 40-year effort will
be certain to make its single currency equal in footing with the
dollar. This might be the EU's hefty innovation for the world
monetary system in this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly Half Loans at Thai Banks Are Non-Performing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Some 46 percent of the total
loans at Thai commercial banks in October are non-performing loans
(NPLs), a Bank of Thailand (BOT) report available Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's eight private commercial banks had loans more than
three-months in arrears amounting to 39.5 percent of the total
loans, or 1.22 trillion baht (33.9 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Eight state-owned commercial banks had NPLs worth 58.3 percent
of the total loans, or 966.3 billion baht (26.8 billion dollars).
Foreign banks had NPLs of 8.05 percent of the total loans.
</P>
<P>
The eight private banks in Thailand are: Bangkok Bank, Thai
Farmers Bank, Siam Commercial Bank, Bank of Ayudhya, Thai Military
Bank, Bank of Asia, Thai Danu Bank and Nakornthon Bank.
</P>
<P>
The eight state-controlled banks are: Krung Thai Bank,
Radanasin Bank, Laem Thong Bank, Union Bank, Bangkok Metropolitan
Bank, Siam City Bank, First Bangkok City Bank and Bangkok Bank of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
BOT said the banking system overall had NPLs worth 40.5 percent
of the total outstanding credit, or more than 2.25 trillion baht
(62.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks are said to have better asset quality because
their loans were focused on few business sectors, mainly financial
institutions and state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The massive jump in NPLs throughout the banking system shows
the desperate need of local institutions for new capital, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
They also estimate that up to 20 billion dollars in new capital
are required by local banks to wipe out bad debt.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on August, the government has pledged up to 300 billion
baht (8.3 billion dollars) in state funds for recapitalizing local
banks in a comprehensive financial reform package.
</P>
<P>
Local institutions are required to make full provision against
projected loan-losses by the end of 2000. Banks and finance
companies unable to meet provision and capital adequacy
requirements must either seek government help or face
nationalization.
</P>
<P>
Finance companies had NPLs totaling 42.3 percent of the
outstanding credit as of October.
</P>
<P>
NPLs in the banking system, including foreign banks, totaled
37.7 percent of the total outstanding credit in September, and
60.6 percent for finance companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
