<HEADLINE> More Child Abuse Cases Reported in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A total of 208 children in
Thailand were found to have been sexually abused this year, a 50-
percent increase over the 138 cases reported last year, a report
from the Child Protection Foundation available Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
Parents, step-fathers, relatives, teachers and monks were the
major offenders, said the foundation.
</P>
<P>
Of the victims 173 were girls, with their age averaged between
four and nine, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In many cases, children were raped many times in a certain
period. Some became pregnant and were expelled from school.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of the abusers have not been punished.
</P>
<P>
According to the foundation, the sharp rise in cases was due to
worsening family relationships.
</P>
<P>
The number of physical abuse cases involving children also
rose, with a total of 220 assault cases being reported to the
foundation this year, against 153 cases last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, 23 children were beaten to death, the report said.
</P>
