<HEADLINE> Two Top KR Defected Leaders Arrive in Phnom Penh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Defecting Khmer Rouge
leaders Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea arrived here Tuesday with
their families by a special military helicopter from Cambodia's
gem-rich northwest city of Pailin.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter landed straight at Prime Minister Hun Sen's
Takhmau residence, about 10 km near the capital. Accompanied with
them is Ieng Sary, who defected to the government in 1996 and now
controls the semi-autonomous zone in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
The two men and their families will be tightly protected by the
government security forces.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen approved Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea's
defection to the government on Friday, which was also supported by
King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said Monday that he does not agree to try
Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, dismissing calls for the defecting
pair to be arrested and prosecuted at an international tribunal.
</P>
<P>
"If the wound does not hurt, should we poke a stick into it and
make it bleed again?" asked Hun Sen. "If we bring the pair to
prison, it could lead to renewed civil war," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said that his policy was in keeping with the 1991 Paris
Peace Accords signed by all factions including the Khmer Rouge.
"The Paris Peace Accords do not ask holding a trial for the Khmer
Rouge. Now we are continuing to implement the Paris Peace Accords,
" added Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
"We should bury old grudges and look ahead into the 21st
century. This is the new government's policy of pacification and
national reconciliation," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
The defection left only the Khmer Rouge's one-legged general Ta
Mok in the jungles with perhaps 100 loyalists. 
</P>
