<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five More Members Back Thai Deputy PM's WTO Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Four more countries and one
region have promised to support Thai Deputy Prime Minister and
Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi in his race for the World
Trade Organization directorship, a foreign ministry official
confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official identified the five WTO members as Panama, Israel,
Hungary, Macao and Poland.
</P>
<P>
Their support gave weight to a recent poll showing that
Supachai was enjoying support from the majority of the WTO's 132
members.
</P>
<P>
Only about 30-40 members, including the United States and
European Union, have remained silent about who their favorite
candidate is.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates are Morocco's ex-trade minister Hassan
Abouyoub, Canada's ex-trade minister Roy MacLaren, and New
Zealand's former prime minister Michael Moore.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Foreign Ministry informed that WTO officials
responsible for the contest will invite all members to show their
formal position by mid-January.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said Monday that his ministry
would write to the countries and regions supporting Thailand,
asking them to continue their support during this "crucial" stage.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident our candidate can act as a good coordinator
between the developed and developing countries," the foreign
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
