<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe Penalties Set for Foreign Exchange Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The National People's Congress
(NPC), China's top legislative body, today adopted a supplementary
provision to the Criminal Law stipulating a maximum sentence of
life imprisonment for major cases involving foreign exchange
infractions.
</P>
<P>
The provision stipulates life sentences for individuals
convicted of purchasing foreign exchange with forged documents,
evading payments or otherwise enaging in illegal trade activities.
</P>
<P>
Criminal acts include forging or altering signed declaration
forms, as well as import proof documents or forms checked by
departments of the foreign exchange administration.
</P>
<P>
Companies are also prohibited from making illegal deposits or
transfers of foreign exchange abroad.
</P>
<P>
Part of foreign exchange infractors will also receive fines as
a concurrent punishment.
</P>
<P>
Staffers working for customs, foreign exchange administration
departments and financial institutions, as well as foreign trade
companies are subject to criminal penalties if convicted of
allowing individuals to use forged documents to purchase foreign
exchange or otherwise evade payment.
</P>
<P>
Criminal penalties also apply to the use of forged or altered
declaration forms and trading foreign exchange at other than
exchanges approved by the government.
</P>
<P>
Confiscated funds and property will be handed over to the state
treasury and fines will range from 5-30 percent of the total
amount of the infraction in question.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian National Assembly Approves Budget Plan for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The National Assembly of
Hungary approved the government's 1999 budget plan Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new budget plan, projected revenues for 1999 will
total 3,136.4 billion forints (14.9 billion U.S. dollars) while
spending is expected to be 3,510.6 billion forints (16.7 billion
dollars), leaving a budget deficit of 374.2 billion forints (1.78
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
A 33 billion forints (157 million dollars) reserve fund was
set up in accordance with the budget plan.
</P>
<P>
The budget plan was passed with 267 votes in favor and 145
votes against. 
</P>
