<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America's Top 10 Events in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Following is a list of
top ten major news events in Latin America in 1998, as selected
and rated by China's official Xinhua News Agency on Monday.
</P>
<P>
1) Despite the financial crisis first originated in Asia and
later in Russia, Latin America closed the year with an economic
growth averaging 2.3 percent, thanks to the countries'joint
adoption of timely measures aimed at resisting the adverse trends
of a world slump. The growth, however, fell below 1997's 5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
2) Re-elected on October 4, President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso became the first head of state ever chosen for a second
term in Brazil's history. Cardoso's new term of office is seen as
highly significant in that it will guarantee the consistence of
his political and economic policies through the end of the 20th
century to the beginning of the next century.
</P>
<P>
3) Former Chilean military leader and lifelong senator Augusto
Pinochet was arrested on October 16 in London at a Spanish
court's request for his extradition on charges that he was
responsible for the killing of a number of Spanish nationals
during his rule.
</P>
<P>
The extradition process filed against the 83-year-old former
head of state has deeply divided Chile's political life and
become an unprecedented case in the international law.
</P>
<P>
4) On October 26, Ecuador and Peru signed in Brasilia a final
peace treaty which ended a century-old border dispute between the
two nations. The pact established a precedent for a peaceful
settlement of conflicts between neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
5) Following three years of lobbying, Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo's government and social activists pressured the
United States into canceling the projected Sierra Blanca nuclear
dump to be located near the US-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
6) Hurricane Mitch, one of the four most destructive storms
registered in the past hundred years, devastated at the end of
October the impoverished Central American nations of Honduras,
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala and Costa Rica, leaving more
than 9,000 people dead and nearly 10,000 injured, while over 2.5
million refugees had to be relocated. Total damage was estimated
at 6.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
7) During his state visit to Britain on October 28 to November
2, Argentine President Carlos Menem discussed pending bilateral
issues with British Prime Minister Tony Blair. The trip was
believed to mark the start of a new era of cooperation between
the two countries and could lead to a possible relief of tension
in the aftermath of the 1982 war over the sovereignty of the
Malvinas (Falklands) islands.
</P>
<P>
8) Venezuelan former Lieutenant Col. Hugo Chavez won the
December 6 presidential election on a landslide victory. The
president-elect was jailed for two years in 1992 for heading a
coup to oust the then President Carlos Andres Perez. He will be
sworn in on February 2, 1999 for a five-year term.
</P>
<P>
9) Argentina and Chile signed on December 15 a treaty on the
delineation of the Continental Ice Shelf, ending their last
border dispute left over by an 1881 pact. The treaty has set
another example of settling border disputes through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
10) For the first time in the past 30 years, Cubans celebrated
on December 25 their first "official" Christmas. The forced
austerity in the country did not dampen the islanders' happiness
or their belief that the current hardship would be overcome. The
Cuban government decided to remove the ban on Christmas following
Pope John Paul II's January visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
