<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Airline Reports Losses Due to EU's Air Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia's national
carrier, the JAT airline, reported Monday that it suffered heavy
economic losses in the past year due to the European Union's air
ban.
</P>
<P>
General Manager Zika Petrovic told reporters the passenger
transport volume in 1998 was 980,000 persons, down 47 percent
from 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cargo transport volume amounted to 3,500 tons,
down 50 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the big slump of both the passenger and cargo
transport volumes to the EU's Vienna decision in June to ban
Yugoslavia's passenger planes from landing in EU member
countries' airports because of the latter's crackdown on
separatist-minded ethnic Albanians in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The EU decision forced JAT to cut 45 percent of the regular
flights, and 40 percent of the workforce were compelled to take
vacation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts Securities Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, adopted the
country's first Securities Law today, which will take effect on
July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 12-chapter, 214-article law governs all aspects of the
securities industry, ranging from the issue and trading of stocks
to the purchase of listed companies, stock exchanges, securities
companies, registration and account settlement agencies, trading
service agencies, self-disciplinary associations, government
regulatory bodies and liabilities for violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
The new law prohibits foreign capital from entering the A-share
market.
</P>
<P>
"A stock investor must present legal documents proving his
identity as a Chinese citizen his qualification as a Chinese legal
person when opening a stock account," the law states.
</P>
<P>
The law provides for a two-tier system for the securities
industry in which securities companies are required to separate
their own accounts from those of their clients. And securities
businesses are separated from banking, trust and insurance
operations, according to the law.
</P>
<P>
According to lawmakers, lessons in the Asian financial and
stock market crisis were drawn in the course of formulating the
law, which contains detailed stipulations on preventing market
risks and standardizing market operations to protect the interests
of investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Pledges Neutrality in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Armed Forces
(ABRI) will stay neutral and maintain an equal distance with all
contestants during next June's general election, ABRI chief Gen.
Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
"ABRI as a social, political and security element will stay
neutral and will not assist any election contestant," Wiranto told
reporters after a meeting with President B.J. Habibie on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He promised that ABRI would only "wear its own jacket" and
would not ally itself with any of the parties in the upcoming
election.
</P>
<P>
By adopting such a stance, ABRI gives a chance to all the
contestants to fully exercise their rights, national newspapers
Tuesday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto also promised that ABRI would only work to secure next
June's poll from disturbances so that contesting parties would be
able to exercise their rights fully.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the security condition in the run-up to the
1999 general election would be more conducive. "Security is needed
not only prior to the general elections but also at all time," he
added.
</P>
<P>
This is the first statement made by Wiranto concerning ABRI's
position in next year's elections. However, the Indonesian
Observer said, it remains to be seen whether or not ABRI will be
able to play a neutral role in the elections.
</P>
<P>
The ABRI had in the past made the same promise of not becoming
involved in elections, but in practice it continued to dabble.
</P>
<P>
During former president Soeharto's 32 years in power, ABRI
directly or indirectly assisted the ruling party Golkar
(Functional Group) to obtain a majority in six consecutive
elections in the period since 1972. This helped Soeharto to remain
to power.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think it is like that. Now, ABRI will really guard
its neutrality," Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Wiranto reported to Habibie preparations for the
coming elections along with Home Affairs Minister Syarwan Hamid,
Coordinating Minister for Political and Security Affairs Feisal
Tandjung, Justice Minister Muladi and Minister/State Secretary
Akbar Tanjung.
</P>
<P>
Hamid told reporters that the general election planned for June
7 would likely be contested by 15 parties.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot predict, but from the 120 parties listed ... the ones
which qualify would probably not be more than 15," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hamid said the president is committed to holding fair and
honest elections next year, once the election bill is approved by
the parliament next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
