<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Conference on Rural Work, which will decide the
major tasks and goals for the development of China's rural economy
next year, opened in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the opening ceremony of the
conference, Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao said that the fundamental task
of the rural work next year and for the coming period is to
seriously implement the guidelines of the Third Plenum of the 15th
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
-- China's first group of 60 supervisors for key State projects
graduated from a four-month training program at Tianjin University
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The supervisors, from the State Development Planning
Commission, will be sent to posts nationwide in January to
strengthen the supervision of the country's major investment and
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Financial institutions, enterprises and individuals in China
can accept and use the Euro in economic, trade and financial
exchanges with 11 members of the European Union (EU) effective
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC), the central bank, and the
State Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE) made the joint
announcement yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji met yesterday with outgoing and
newly-appointed ambassadors to China from 17 countries.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing ambassadors include those of Madagascar, Uganda,
Jordan, Mauritania, Germany, Cyprus and Colombia, and the new
ambassadors are from Japan, Moldova, the Sudan, Bosnia
Herzegovina, Italy, Kenya, Slovakia, Nepal, Turkey and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
