<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: Tax Evasion in Italy Eats Fiscal Revenues in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) said Monday that tax evasion and avoidance in Italy caused
fiscal loss equal to 12.6 percent of its gross domestic
product(GDP), about 250 trillion lire (152 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
IMF reports said that Italy's small and medium businesses
lacked in their obligations to the financial administration in
failing to report revenues which account for an estimated 58.7
percent of all potential taxable income.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said Italy had become a country with the
heaviest tax burden on back in Europe. Direct taxes levied
accounted for 12.5 percent of GDP in Europe in 1997 and for 15.9
percent of GDP in Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former NPC Deputy Applauds Rural Reforms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China's rural reform has
greatly benefited the rural population, providing a better life
for Chinese farmers.
</P>
<P>
"The same efforts now may have totally different results due to
the change of policies," said Wang Zuoshan, a deputy to the
National People's Congress during China's "Cultural Revolution"
(1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
Wang was the head of Xiaojin Village in Baodi County in
Tianjin, about 100 kilometers from Beijing, for 18 years. The
village was famous for its revolutionary ardor during the
"Cultural Revolution."
</P>
<P>
The 63-year-old former village head was unwilling to talk about
his leadership in that period, saying that he didn't catch the
good times when he served as the village head.
</P>
<P>
The old man has been preoccupied with the question why he and
the villagers worked so hard in the past, yet their toil didn't
pay off.
</P>
<P>
"We did as much as we could at that time, but our village was
much poorer than it is now," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, one laborer earned less than one yuan (0.12
U.S. dollar) a day, but that still represented the highest income
in the whole suburban areas of Tianjin. Last year, the average per
capita income in the village reached 3,800 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Our village used to be the best-equipped in the region," Wang
said. "We had eight walking tractors and one large tractor in the
past, which made other villages envious of us."
</P>
<P>
Today, farm work in the village is done by hundreds of motor
vehicles. Wheat harvesting which used to take a month can now be
finished within a week, and the village has also improved its
fields to make them invulnerable to natural disasters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former NPC Deputy Applauds Rural Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Nowadays, most of the young people don't work in the fields
anymore, they work in the township enterprises, and some go out to
big cities to work on construction sites," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
In many of China's rural areas, township enterprises
contribute a large proportion to the villagers' incomes.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of the village's income comes from
agriculture now, and those who don't work in the factories are
mostly engaged in cash-crop planting and livestock breeding.
</P>
<P>
"We used to grow what we ate, but now we are focusing on the
most profitable crops," Wang said. At present, Xiaojin Village
mainly grows onion and garlic.
</P>
<P>
"We were not allowed to grow these crops in the past, they were
regarded as part of the capitalist economy. I knew that's not
right, and that's why the harder I tried to implement those
policies, the worse things became," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Wang's two sons are now engaged in businesses which were
criticized and forbidden under Wang's leadership in the past. The
elder son has opened a factory repairing agricultural machinery,
and the younger son owns a chicken farm.
</P>
<P>
Wang and his wife now live peacefully in their own house. They
have three children, two sons and a daughter, and the daughter is
working in the seat of Baodi County. Each month, Wang receives a
pension of 80 yuan for his past services from the County
Government.
</P>
<P>
Although living in a small village of only 600 people, Wang
keeps a close eye on the outside world. He said that reform had
made the village a part of the world, and he is intent on all the
information concerning the village. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
