<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Have Drawn Up a Lunar Mining Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- A team of geologists led by
Jeffrey Johnson of the US Geological Survey said that they have
worked out a map of the lunar deposits of helium-3, making the
prospect of the commercial exploitation of the Moon moving a step
closer, said the British weekly the New Scientist.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this valuable isotope of helium might become
the source of nuclear energy in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The geologists said they identified three factors that
influence the concentration of the gas. The first is the age of
rock: helium-3 should be concentrated in old soils, since they
have been exposed to the solar wind for much longer. The second
factor is the type of rock: titanium-containing minerals,
principally ilmenite, are particularly effective at trapping
helium-3. The last factor is the strength of the solar wind:
places where it is strongest will accumulate more helium-3.
</P>
<P>
Based on the above three factors, the geologists have deduced
that the best places possible to find helium-3 are the Mare
Tranquillitatis and the Oceanus Procellarum on the near side of
Moon, and the Tsiolkovskiy crater and the Mare Orientale on the
far side.
</P>
<P>
According to their estimates, there is about a million tons
of helium-3 on the Moon as a whole, compared with an estimated 20
tons in the Earth's deep interior.
</P>
<P>
Researchers say a nuclear fusion reactor exploiting the fusion
of helium-3 and deuterium would generate very few neutrons. This
has the great advantage of not making the containment vessel
radioactive, as happens in a conventional tritium-deuterium fusion
reactor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Visits Greece Over Missile Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides left for Greece Monday afternoon to meet Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis on the future of the Russian S-300
missiles ordered by Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly before his departure, Clerides said the
National Council, the top advisory body to the president on Cyprus
issue, will meet Tuesday to decide the issue after his return
from Greece.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said only a decision that can be unanimously approved
by the council "will be respected."
</P>
<P>
If not, the final decision will be made by himself, the
president of the republic, Clerides added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the surface-to-air missiles in January 1997 in a
bid to cement its air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the close ally of independence-seeking Turkish Cypriots
in Cyprus, has threatened to launch a preemptive strike on the
missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., the U.S. and Britain have also expressed opposition
to the deployment of the missiles, which they said will increase
tensions on the Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides also pointed out that there have been no suggestions
for a referendum on the future of the missiles, saying "a
referendum will not serve national interests." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Says It Downs Enemy Warplane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced that its air
defense force has shot down an enemy warplane on Monday.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi Defense Ministry spokesman said Monday evening that
the enemy warplane might be a U.S. one, the Iraqi News Agency
(INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
No further details were given by the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. said its F-16c's policing Iraq's northern no-fly zone
were fired at by Iraqi surface-to-air missiles, signalling an
escalation of confrontation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. warplanes responded with heat-seeking missiles to
destroy the Iraqi military post. Baghdad said earlier that four
soldiers were killed and seven wounded.
</P>
<P>
The INA report said the U.S. did not announce one of its
warplanes was shot down because it hoped the pilot, if survived,
could "steal out of Iraq," or that his corpse, if dead, could be
taken back "surreptitiously" by U.S. "claws."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981229.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2130 GMT, December 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- An explosion occurred on a fuel tanker of the Iranian
navy Sunday afternoon, killing five crew members and injured 10
others.
</P>
<P>
So far the reason for the incident has not been
established. The tanker anchored at the naval forces jetty in the
southern port Bandar Abass, the Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA) reported on Monday. (BC-Iran-Explosion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was
confronted with more challenges from the right wing Monday as a
hard-line member of his coalition quitted the Likud and declared
his candidacy for the premiership in the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
Benny Begin, the son of Likud founder Menachem Begin,
announced that he will form a new party that will flank the Likud
from the right in the elections. He once served as science
minister in Netanyahu's government but resigned over differences
in ideology and personality. (BC-Israel-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Four Iraqi soldiers were killed and seven others
injured in U.S. missile attacks on Monday, said an Iraqi military
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said U.S. war planes flying from Turkey violated
Iraqi air space in the so-called no-fly zone in the north of Iraq
and launched missiles at Iraqi air defense positions.
(BC-Iraq-US-Missile Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Arab foreign ministerial meeting slated for
Wednesday has been put off to next month due to the rifts among
the Gulf states, Arab League (AL) Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid told reporters that after intensive contacts and
consultations over the past 24 hours, the Arab countries have
agreed to convene the meeting in Cairo on January 24.
(BC-Egypt-Arab League-FM Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Violent clashes broke out at a Palestinian village
in the West Bank Monday as Israeli soldiers tore down two
Palestinian houses as "illegal buildings."
</P>
<P>
Israeli TV Channel One showed a middle-aged Palestinian man, a
child in his arms, was at the door of his house trying to block
the soldiers. He fell to the ground when the soldiers forcefully
evicted him.
</P>
<P>
A bulldozer soon leveled the house and a shack. Angered, dozens
of villagers threw stones at the soldiers, who responded with tear
gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said an Israeli soldier and a border policeman
were injured in the clashes. At least one Palestinian youth was
seen bleeding on his forehead on the TV.
(BC-Israel-Palestinians-Clash) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
